# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quic-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC improves performance of connection-oriented web applications that previously relied on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:quic-protocol/quic] It does this by establishing a number of multiplexed connections between two endpoints using User Datagram Protocol (UDP), and it is designed to obsolete TCP at the transport layer for many applications.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Although its name was initially proposed as an acronym for *Quick UDP Internet Connections*, in IETF's use of the word *QUIC* is not an acronym; it is simply the name of the protocol.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC works hand-in-hand with HTTP/3's multiplexed connections, allowing multiple streams of data to reach all the endpoints independently, and hence independent of packet losses involving other streams.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In contrast, HTTP/2, which is carried over TCP, can suffer head-of-line-blocking delays if multiple streams are multiplexed on a TCP connection and any of the TCP packets on that connection are delayed or lost.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC's secondary goals include reduced connection and transport latency, and bandwidth estimation in each direction to avoid congestion.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] It also moves congestion control algorithms into the user space at both endpoints, rather than the kernel space, which is claimed to allow these algorithms to improve more rapidly.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Additionally, the protocol can be extended with forward error correction (FEC) to further improve performance when errors are expected.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] It is designed with the intention of avoiding protocol ossification.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In June 2015, an Internet Draft of a specification for QUIC was submitted to the IETF for standardization.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] A QUIC working group was established in 2016.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In October 2018, the IETF's HTTP and QUIC Working Groups jointly decided to call the HTTP mapping over QUIC "HTTP/3" in advance of making it a worldwide standard.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In May 2021, the IETF standardized QUIC in RFC 9000, supported by RFC 8999, 9001 and 9002.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Transmission Control Protocol, or TCP, aims to provide an interface for sending streams of data between two endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Data is sent to the TCP system, which ensures it reaches the other end in the exact same form; if any discrepancies occur, the connection will signal an error condition.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] To do this, TCP breaks up the data into network packets and adds small amounts of data to each packet.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This additional data includes a sequence number that is used to detect packets that are lost or arrive out of order, and a checksum that allows the errors within packet data to be detected.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] When either problem occurs, TCP uses automatic repeat request (ARQ) to ask the sender to re-send the lost or damaged packet.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In most implementations, TCP will see any error on a connection as a blocking operation, stopping further transfers until the error is resolved or the connection is considered failed.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] If a single connection is being used to send multiple streams of data, as is the case in the HTTP/2 protocol, all of these streams are blocked although only one of them might have a problem.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] For instance, if a single error occurs while downloading a GIF image used for a favicon, the entire rest of the page will wait while that problem is resolved.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This phenomenon is known as head-of-line blocking.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] As the TCP system is designed to look like a "data pipe", or stream, it deliberately has little information regarding the data it transmits.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] If that data has additional requirements, like encryption using TLS, this must be set up by systems running on top of TCP, using TCP to communicate with similar software on the other end of the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Each of these sorts of setup tasks requires its own handshake process.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This often requires several round-trips of requests and responses until the connection is established.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Due to the inherent latency of long-distance communications, this can add significant delay to the overall transmission.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] TCP has suffered from protocol ossification, due to its wire image being in cleartext and hence visible to and malleable by middleboxes.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] One measurement found that a third of paths across the Internet encounter at least one intermediary that modifies TCP metadata, and 6.5% of paths encounter harmful ossifying effects from intermediaries.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Extensions to TCP have been affected: the design of Multipath TCP (MPTCP) was constrained by middlebox behaviour, and the deployment of TCP Fast Open has been likewise hindered.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In the context of supporting encrypted HTTP traffic, QUIC serves a role similar to that of TCP, but with reduced latency during connection setup and more efficient loss recovery when multiple HTTP streams are multiplexed over a single connection.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] It does this primarily through two changes that rely on the understanding of the behaviour of HTTP traffic.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The first change is to greatly reduce overhead during connection setup.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] As most HTTP connections will demand TLS, QUIC makes the exchange of setup keys and listing of supported protocols part of the initial handshake process.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] When a client opens a connection, the response packet includes the data needed for future packets to use encryption.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This eliminates the need to set up an unencrypted *pipe* and then negotiate the security protocol as separate steps.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Other protocols can be serviced in the same way, combining multiple steps into a single request–response pair.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This data can then be used both for following requests in the initial setup and future requests that would otherwise be negotiated as separate connections.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The second change is to use UDP rather than TCP as its basis, which does not include loss recovery.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Instead, each QUIC stream is separately flow-controlled, and lost data is retransmitted at the level of QUIC, not UDP.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This means that if an error occurs in one stream, like the favicon example above, the protocol stack can continue servicing other streams independently.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This can be very useful in improving performance on error-prone links, as in most cases considerable additional data may be received before TCP notices a packet is missing or broken, and all of this data is blocked or even flushed while the error is corrected.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In QUIC, this data is free to be processed while the single multiplexed stream is repaired.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC includes a number of other changes that improve overall latency and throughput.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] For instance, the packets are encrypted individually, so that they do not result in the encrypted data waiting for partial packets.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This is not generally possible under TCP, where the encryption records are in a bytestream and the protocol stack is unaware of higher-layer boundaries within this stream.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] These can be negotiated by the layers running on top, but QUIC aims to do all of this in a single handshake process.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Another goal of the QUIC system was to improve performance during network-switching events, like what happens when a user of a mobile device moves from a local Wi-Fi hotspot to a mobile network.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] When this occurs on TCP, a lengthy process starts where every existing connection times out one-by-one and is then re-established on demand.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] To solve this problem, QUIC includes a connection identifier to uniquely identify the connection to the server regardless of source.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This allows the connection to be re-established simply by sending a packet, which always contains this ID, as the original connection ID will still be valid even if the user's IP address changes.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC can be implemented in the application space, as opposed to being in the operating system kernel.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This generally invokes additional overhead due to context switches as data is moved between applications.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] However, in the case of QUIC, the protocol stack is intended to be used by a single application, with each application using QUIC having its own connections hosted on UDP.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Ultimately the difference could be very small because much of the overall HTTP/2 stack is already in the applications (or their libraries, more commonly).
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Placing the remaining parts in those libraries, essentially the error correction, has little effect on the HTTP/2 stack's size or overall complexity.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This organization allows future changes to be made more easily as it does not require changes to the kernel for updates.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] One of QUIC's longer-term goals is to add new systems for forward error correction (FEC) and improved congestion control.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] One concern about the move from TCP to UDP is that TCP is widely adopted and many of the "middleboxes" in the Internet infrastructure are tuned for TCP and rate-limit or even block UDP.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Google carried out a number of exploratory experiments to characterize this and found that only a small number of connections were blocked in this manner.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] This led to the use of a system for rapid fallback to TCP; Chromium's network stack starts both a QUIC and a conventional TCP connection at the same time, which allows it to fall back with negligible latency.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC has been specifically designed to be deployable and evolvable and to have anti-ossification properties; it is the first IETF transport protocol to deliberately minimise its wire image for these ends.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Beyond encrypted headers, it is 'greased' and it has protocol invariants explicitly specified.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The security layer of QUIC is based on TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Earlier insecure protocols such as TLS 1.0 are not allowed in a QUIC stack.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The protocol originally developed by Google, known as gQUIC, was first deployed around 2012 and later brought to the IETF.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] However, the version of QUIC standardized by the IETF is significantly different from the earlier Google implementation.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Google's QUIC was initially designed as a general-purpose web protocol and was deployed mainly to support HTTP and HTTPS in Chromium, using its own encryption and transport mechanisms.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In contrast, the IETF QUIC protocol has been redeveloped as a general-purpose transport protocol that uses standard TLS 1.3 for its cryptographic handshake and incorporates a modular packet and connection design intended for broader interoperability.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Chromium developers have continued to follow the progress of IETF QUIC standardization and have worked to adopt and comply with the evolving Internet standards for QUIC within Chromium.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The transition to IETF QUIC in Chrome began progressing publicly around 2020.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] QUIC was developed with HTTP in mind, and HTTP/3 was its first application.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] DNS-over-QUIC is an application of QUIC to name resolution, providing security for data transferred between resolvers similar to DNS-over-TLS.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The IETF is developing applications of QUIC for secure network tunnelling and streaming media delivery.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] XMPP has experimentally been adapted to use QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Another application is SMB over QUIC, which, according to Microsoft, can offer an "SMB VPN" without affecting the user experience.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] SMB clients use TCP by default and will attempt QUIC if the TCP attempt fails or if intentionally requiring QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The QUIC code was experimentally developed in Google Chrome starting in 2012, and was announced as part of Chromium version 29 (released on August 20, 2013).
[src:quic-protocol/quic] It is currently enabled by default in Chromium and Chrome.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Apple added experimental support in the WebKit engine through the Safari Technology Preview 104 in April 2020.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Official support was added in Safari 14, included in macOS Big Sur and iOS 14, but the feature needed to be turned on manually.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] It was later enabled by default in Safari 16.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The cronet library for QUIC and other protocols is available to Android applications as a module loadable via Google Play Services.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] cURL 7.66, released 11 September 2019, supports HTTP/3 (and thus QUIC).
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In October 2020, Facebook announced that it has successfully migrated its apps, including Instagram, and server infrastructure to QUIC, with already 75% of its Internet traffic using QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] All mobile apps from Google support QUIC, including YouTube and Gmail.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] As of 2017, there are several actively maintained implementations.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Google servers support QUIC and Google has published a prototype server.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Akamai Technologies has supported QUIC since July 2016.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] A Go implementation called quic-go is also available, and powers experimental QUIC support in the Caddy server.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] On July 11, 2017, LiteSpeed Technologies officially began supporting QUIC in their load balancer (WebADC) and LiteSpeed Web Server products.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] As of October 2019, 88.6% of QUIC websites used LiteSpeed and 10.8% used Nginx.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Although at first only Google servers supported HTTP-over-QUIC connections, Facebook also launched the technology in 2018, and Cloudflare has been offering QUIC support on a beta basis since 2018.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The HAProxy load balancer added experimental support for QUIC in March 2022 and declared it production-ready in March 2023.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] As of April 2023, 8.9% of all websites use QUIC, up from 5% in March 2021.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Microsoft Windows Server 2022 supports both HTTP/3 and SMB over QUIC protocols via MsQuic.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] The Application Delivery Controller of Citrix (Citrix ADC, NetScaler) can function as a QUIC proxy since version 13.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] In addition, there are several stale community projects: libquic was created by extracting the Chromium implementation of QUIC and modifying it to minimize dependency requirements, and goquic provides Go bindings of libquic.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] Finally, quic-reverse-proxy is a Docker image that acts as a reverse proxy server, translating QUIC requests into plain HTTP that can be understood by the origin server.
[src:quic-protocol/quic] .NET 5 introduces experimental support for QUIC using the MsQuic library.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document defines the core of the QUIC transport protocol.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC provides applications with flow-controlled streams for structured communication, low-latency connection establishment, and network path migration.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC includes security measures that ensure confidentiality, integrity, and availability in a range of deployment circumstances.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document is a product of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] It represents the consensus of the IETF community.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] It has received public review and has been approved for publication by the Internet Engineering Steering Group (IESG).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Copyright (c) 2021 IETF Trust and the persons identified as the document authors.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document is subject to BCP 78 and the IETF Trust's Legal Provisions Relating to IETF Documents (https://trustee.ietf.org/license-info) in effect on the date of publication of this document.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Please review these documents carefully, as they describe your rights and restrictions with respect to this document.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC is a secure general-purpose transport protocol.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The QUIC handshake combines negotiation of cryptographic and transport parameters.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC integrates the TLS handshake [TLS13], although using a customized framing for protecting packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The integration of TLS and QUIC is described in more detail in [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The handshake is structured to permit the exchange of application data as soon as possible.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Endpoints communicate in QUIC by exchanging QUIC packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Most packets contain frames, which carry control information and application data between endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC authenticates the entirety of each packet and encrypts as much of each packet as is practical.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Application protocols exchange information over a QUIC connection via streams, which are ordered sequences of bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Two types of streams can be created: bidirectional streams, which allow both endpoints to send data; and unidirectional streams, which allow a single endpoint to send data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC provides the necessary feedback to implement reliable delivery and congestion control.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An algorithm for detecting and recovering from loss of data is described in Section 6 of [QUIC-RECOVERY].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC depends on congestion control to avoid network congestion.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC connections are not strictly bound to a single network path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Connection migration uses connection identifiers to allow connections to transfer to a new network path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Only clients are able to migrate in this version of QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Once established, multiple options are provided for connection termination.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] To refer to QUIC version 1, cite this document.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The transport protocol described by this document.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An entity that can participate in a QUIC connection by generating, receiving, and processing QUIC packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A complete processable unit of QUIC that can be encapsulated in a UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A QUIC packet that contains frames other than ACK, PADDING, and CONNECTION_CLOSE.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A unit of structured protocol information.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] There are multiple frame types, each of which carries different information.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An identifier that is used to identify a QUIC connection at an endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Each endpoint selects one or more connection IDs for its peer to include in packets sent towards the endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A unidirectional or bidirectional channel of ordered bytes within a QUIC connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document uses the terms "QUIC packets", "UDP datagrams", and "IP packets" to refer to the units of the respective protocols.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Packet and frame diagrams in this document use a custom format.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The purpose of this format is to summarize, not define, protocol elements.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Complex fields are named and then followed by a list of fields surrounded by a pair of matching braces.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Individual fields include length information, plus indications about fixed value, optionality, or repetitions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document uses network byte order (that is, big endian) values.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] When a single-bit field is referenced in prose, the position of that field can be clarified by using the value of the byte that carries the field with the field's value set.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Streams in QUIC provide a lightweight, ordered byte-stream abstraction to an application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Other processes associated with stream management -- ending, canceling, and managing flow control -- are all designed to impose minimal overheads.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] For instance, a single STREAM frame (Section 19.8) can open, carry data for, and close a stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Streams can be created by either endpoint, can concurrently send data interleaved with other streams, and can be canceled.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Streams can be unidirectional or bidirectional.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Unidirectional streams carry data in one direction: from the initiator of the stream to its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Streams are identified within a connection by a numeric value, referred to as the stream ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A stream ID is a 62-bit integer (0 to 262-1) that is unique for all streams on a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Stream IDs are encoded as variable-length integers; see Section 16.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The least significant bit (0x01) of the stream ID identifies the initiator of the stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The stream space for each type begins at the minimum value (0x00 through 0x03, respectively); successive streams of each type are created with numerically increasing stream IDs.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] STREAM frames (Section 19.8) encapsulate data sent by an application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Endpoints MUST be able to deliver stream data to an application as an ordered byte stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC makes no specific allowances for delivery of stream data out of order.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint could receive data for a stream at the same stream offset multiple times.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Data that has already been received can be discarded.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Streams are an ordered byte-stream abstraction with no other structure visible to QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint MUST NOT send data on any stream without ensuring that it is within the flow control limits set by its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC does not provide a mechanism for exchanging prioritization information.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A QUIC implementation SHOULD provide ways in which an application can indicate the relative priority of streams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document does not define an API for QUIC; it instead defines a set of functions on streams that application protocols can rely upon.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An application protocol can assume that a QUIC implementation provides an interface that includes the operations described in this section.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This section describes streams in terms of their send or receive components.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Unidirectional streams use either the sending or receiving state machine, depending on the stream type and endpoint role.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Bidirectional streams use both state machines at both endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] For the most part, the use of these state machines is the same whether the stream is unidirectional or bidirectional.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The state machines shown in this section are largely informative.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This document uses stream states to describe rules for when and how different types of frames can be sent and the reactions that are expected when different types of frames are received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Though these state machines are intended to be useful in implementing QUIC, these states are not intended to constrain implementations.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The sending part of a stream that the endpoint initiates (types 0 and 2 for clients, 1 and 3 for servers) is opened by the application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The "Ready" state represents a newly created stream that is able to accept data from the application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Sending the first STREAM or STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED frame causes a sending part of a stream to enter the "Send" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] In the "Send" state, an endpoint transmits -- and retransmits as necessary -- stream data in STREAM frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The endpoint respects the flow control limits set by its peer and continues to accept and process MAX_STREAM_DATA frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] After the application indicates that all stream data has been sent and a STREAM frame containing the FIN bit is sent, the sending part of the stream enters the "Data Sent" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] From this state, the endpoint only retransmits stream data as necessary.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The endpoint does not need to check flow control limits or send STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED frames for a stream in this state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] MAX_STREAM_DATA frames might be received until the peer receives the final stream offset.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] From any state that is one of "Ready", "Send", or "Data Sent", an application can signal that it wishes to abandon transmission of stream data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Alternatively, an endpoint might receive a STOP_SENDING frame from its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Figure 3 shows the states for the part of a stream that receives data from a peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The states for a receiving part of a stream mirror only some of the states of the sending part of the stream at the peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The receiving part of a stream does not track states on the sending part that cannot be observed, such as the "Ready" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The receiving part of a stream initiated by a peer (types 1 and 3 for a client, or 0 and 2 for a server) is created when the first STREAM, STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED, or RESET_STREAM frame is received for that stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] For bidirectional streams initiated by a peer, receipt of a MAX_STREAM_DATA or STOP_SENDING frame for the sending part of the stream also creates the receiving part.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint opens a bidirectional stream when a MAX_STREAM_DATA or STOP_SENDING frame is received from the peer for that stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Receiving a MAX_STREAM_DATA frame for an unopened stream indicates that the remote peer has opened the stream and is providing flow control credit.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Receiving a STOP_SENDING frame for an unopened stream indicates that the remote peer no longer wishes to receive data on this stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Before a stream is created, all streams of the same type with lower-numbered stream IDs MUST be created.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] In the "Recv" state, the endpoint receives STREAM and STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Incoming data is buffered and can be reassembled into the correct order for delivery to the application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] When a STREAM frame with a FIN bit is received, the final size of the stream is known; see Section 4.5.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The receiving part of the stream then enters the "Size Known" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Once all data for the stream has been received, the receiving part enters the "Data Recvd" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This might happen as a result of receiving the same STREAM frame that causes the transition to "Size Known".
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The "Data Recvd" state persists until stream data has been delivered to the application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Receiving a RESET_STREAM frame in the "Recv" or "Size Known" state causes the stream to enter the "Reset Recvd" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] It is possible that all stream data has already been received when a RESET_STREAM is received (that is, in the "Data Recvd" state).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Similarly, it is possible for remaining stream data to arrive after receiving a RESET_STREAM frame (the "Reset Recvd" state).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Sending a RESET_STREAM means that an endpoint cannot guarantee delivery of stream data; however, there is no requirement that stream data not be delivered if a RESET_STREAM is received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An implementation MAY interrupt delivery of stream data, discard any data that was not consumed, and signal the receipt of the RESET_STREAM.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A RESET_STREAM signal might be suppressed or withheld if stream data is completely received and is buffered to be read by the application.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A sender MUST NOT send any of these frames from a terminal state ("Data Recvd" or "Reset Recvd").
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A sender MUST NOT send a STREAM or STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED frame for a stream in the "Reset Sent" state or any terminal state -- that is, after sending a RESET_STREAM frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The receiver only sends MAX_STREAM_DATA frames in the "Recv" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver MAY send a STOP_SENDING frame in any state where it has not received a RESET_STREAM frame -- that is, states other than "Reset Recvd" or "Reset Read".
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] However, there is little value in sending a STOP_SENDING frame in the "Data Recvd" state, as all stream data has been received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A bidirectional stream is composed of sending and receiving parts.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Implementations can represent states of the bidirectional stream as composites of sending and receiving stream states.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Table 2 shows a more complex mapping of bidirectional stream states that loosely correspond to the stream states defined in HTTP/2 [HTTP2].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This shows that multiple states on sending or receiving parts of streams are mapped to the same composite state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] If the stream is in the "Recv" or "Size Known" state, the transport SHOULD signal this by sending a STOP_SENDING frame to prompt closure of the stream in the opposite direction.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A STOP_SENDING frame requests that the receiving endpoint send a RESET_STREAM frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint that receives a STOP_SENDING frame MUST send a RESET_STREAM frame if the stream is in the "Ready" or "Send" state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] If the stream is in the "Data Sent" state, the endpoint MAY defer sending the RESET_STREAM frame until the packets containing outstanding data are acknowledged or declared lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint SHOULD copy the error code from the STOP_SENDING frame to the RESET_STREAM frame it sends, but it can use any application error code.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] STOP_SENDING SHOULD only be sent for a stream that has not been reset by the peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint is expected to send another STOP_SENDING frame if a packet containing a previous STOP_SENDING is lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Receivers need to limit the amount of data that they are required to buffer, in order to prevent a fast sender from overwhelming them or a malicious sender from consuming a large amount of memory.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] To enable a receiver to limit memory commitments for a connection, streams are flow controlled both individually and across a connection as a whole.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Data sent in CRYPTO frames is not flow controlled in the same way as stream data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC relies on the cryptographic protocol implementation to avoid excessive buffering of data; see [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] QUIC employs a limit-based flow control scheme where a receiver advertises the limit of total bytes it is prepared to receive on a given stream or for the entire connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver sets initial limits for all streams through transport parameters during the handshake (Section 7.4).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver can advertise a larger limit for a stream by sending a MAX_STREAM_DATA frame with the corresponding stream ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A MAX_STREAM_DATA frame indicates the maximum absolute byte offset of a stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver can advertise a larger limit for a connection by sending a MAX_DATA frame, which indicates the maximum of the sum of the absolute byte offsets of all streams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver maintains a cumulative sum of bytes received on all streams, which is used to check for violations of the advertised connection or stream data limits.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] If a sender has sent data up to the limit, it will be unable to send new data and is considered blocked.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A sender SHOULD send a STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED or DATA_BLOCKED frame to indicate to the receiver that it has data to write but is blocked by flow control limits.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] If a sender is blocked for a period longer than the idle timeout (Section 10.1), the receiver might close the connection even when the sender has data that is available for transmission.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Control frames contribute to connection overhead.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Therefore, frequently sending MAX_STREAM_DATA and MAX_DATA frames with small changes is undesirable.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] On the other hand, if updates are less frequent, larger increments to limits are necessary to avoid blocking a sender, requiring larger resource commitments at the receiver.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver can use an autotuning mechanism to tune the frequency and amount of advertised additional credit based on a round-trip time estimate and the rate at which the receiving application consumes data, similar to common TCP implementations.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A blocked sender is not required to send STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED or DATA_BLOCKED frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Therefore, a receiver MUST NOT wait for a STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED or DATA_BLOCKED frame before sending a MAX_STREAM_DATA or MAX_DATA frame; doing so could result in the sender being blocked for the rest of the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Sending timely updates of flow control limits can improve performance.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Sending packets only to provide flow control updates can increase network load and adversely affect performance.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] RESET_STREAM terminates one direction of a stream abruptly.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] For a bidirectional stream, RESET_STREAM has no effect on data flow in the opposite direction.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The final size is the amount of flow control credit that is consumed by a stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Assuming that every contiguous byte on the stream was sent once, the final size is the number of bytes sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A sender always communicates the final size of a stream to the receiver reliably, no matter how the stream is terminated.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] The final size is the sum of the Offset and Length fields of a STREAM frame with a FIN flag, noting that these fields might be implicit.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Alternatively, the Final Size field of a RESET_STREAM frame carries this value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint will know the final size for a stream when the receiving part of the stream enters the "Size Known" or "Reset Recvd" state (Section 3).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Once a final size for a stream is known, it cannot change.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] If a RESET_STREAM or STREAM frame is received indicating a change in the final size for the stream, an endpoint SHOULD respond with an error of type FINAL_SIZE_ERROR; see Section 11 for details on error handling.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] A receiver SHOULD treat receipt of data at or beyond the final size as an error of type FINAL_SIZE_ERROR, even after a stream is closed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint limits the cumulative number of incoming streams a peer can open.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Only streams with a stream ID less than `(max_streams * 4 + first_stream_id_of_type)` can be opened; see Table 1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Initial limits are set in the transport parameters; see Section 18.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Subsequent limits are advertised using MAX_STREAMS frames; see Section 19.11.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] If a max_streams transport parameter or a MAX_STREAMS frame is received with a value greater than 260, this would allow a maximum stream ID that cannot be expressed as a variable-length integer; see Section 16.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Endpoints MUST NOT exceed the limit set by their peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] Once a receiver advertises a stream limit using the MAX_STREAMS frame, advertising a smaller limit has no effect.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] As with stream and connection flow control, this document leaves implementations to decide when and how many streams should be advertised to a peer via MAX_STREAMS.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] An endpoint that is unable to open a new stream due to the peer's limits SHOULD send a STREAMS_BLOCKED frame (Section 19.14).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p01] This signal is considered useful for debugging.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Each connection starts with a handshake phase, during which the two endpoints establish a shared secret using the cryptographic handshake protocol [QUIC-TLS] and negotiate the application protocol.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An application protocol can use the connection during the handshake phase with some limitations.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] 0-RTT allows application data to be sent by a client before receiving a response from the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] However, 0-RTT provides no protection against replay attacks; see Section 9.2 of [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server can also send application data to a client before it receives the final cryptographic handshake messages that allow it to confirm the identity and liveness of the client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The use of connection IDs (Section 5.1) allows connections to migrate to a new network path, both as a direct choice of an endpoint and when forced by a change in a middlebox.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Each connection possesses a set of connection identifiers, or connection IDs, each of which can identify the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The primary function of a connection ID is to ensure that changes in addressing at lower protocol layers (UDP, IP) do not cause packets for a QUIC connection to be delivered to the wrong endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Connection IDs MUST NOT contain any information that can be used by an external observer (that is, one that does not cooperate with the issuer) to correlate them with other connection IDs for the same connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Packets with long headers include Source Connection ID and Destination Connection ID fields.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Packets with short headers (Section 17.3) only include the Destination Connection ID and omit the explicit length.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The length of the Destination Connection ID field is expected to be known to endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints using a load balancer that routes based on connection ID could agree with the load balancer on a fixed length for connection IDs or agree on an encoding scheme.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A zero-length connection ID can be used when a connection ID is not needed to route to the correct endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] However, multiplexing connections on the same local IP address and port while using zero-length connection IDs will cause failures in the presence of peer connection migration, NAT rebinding, and client port reuse.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] When an endpoint uses a non-zero-length connection ID, it needs to ensure that the peer has a supply of connection IDs from which to choose for packets sent to the endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Each connection ID has an associated sequence number to assist in detecting when NEW_CONNECTION_ID or RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frames refer to the same value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The initial connection ID issued by an endpoint is sent in the Source Connection ID field of the long packet header (Section 17.2) during the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The sequence number of the initial connection ID is 0.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Additional connection IDs are communicated to the peer using NEW_CONNECTION_ID frames (Section 19.15).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The sequence number on each newly issued connection ID MUST increase by 1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] When an endpoint issues a connection ID, it MUST accept packets that carry this connection ID for the duration of the connection or until its peer invalidates the connection ID via a RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frame (Section 19.16).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Connection IDs that are issued and not retired are considered active; any active connection ID is valid for use with the current connection at any time, in any packet type.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint SHOULD ensure that its peer has a sufficient number of available and unused connection IDs.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints advertise the number of active connection IDs they are willing to maintain using the active_connection_id_limit transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint MUST NOT provide more connection IDs than the peer's limit.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A NEW_CONNECTION_ID frame might cause an endpoint to add some active connection IDs and retire others based on the value of the Retire Prior To field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint SHOULD supply a new connection ID when the peer retires a connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If an endpoint provided fewer connection IDs than the peer's active_connection_id_limit, it MAY supply a new connection ID when it receives a packet with a previously unused connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint MAY limit the total number of connection IDs issued for each connection to avoid the risk of running out of connection IDs; see Section 10.3.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint that selects a zero-length connection ID during the handshake cannot issue a new connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint can change the connection ID it uses for a peer to another available one at any time during the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint maintains a set of connection IDs received from its peer, any of which it can use when sending packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] When the endpoint wishes to remove a connection ID from use, it sends a RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frame to its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] As discussed in Section 9.5, endpoints limit the use of a connection ID to packets sent from a single local address to a single destination address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint might need to stop accepting previously issued connection IDs in certain circumstances.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Such an endpoint can cause its peer to retire connection IDs by sending a NEW_CONNECTION_ID frame with an increased Retire Prior To field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The endpoint SHOULD continue to accept the previously issued connection IDs until they are retired by the peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Upon receipt of an increased Retire Prior To field, the peer MUST stop using the corresponding connection IDs and retire them with RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frames before adding the newly provided connection ID to the set of active connection IDs.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This ordering allows an endpoint to replace all active connection IDs without the possibility of a peer having no available connection IDs and without exceeding the limit the peer sets in the active_connection_id_limit transport parameter; see Section 18.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint SHOULD limit the number of connection IDs it has retired locally for which RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frames have not yet been acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint SHOULD allow for sending and tracking a number of RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frames of at least twice the value of the active_connection_id_limit transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Incoming packets are classified on receipt.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints try to associate a packet with an existing connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If the packet has a non-zero-length Destination Connection ID corresponding to an existing connection, QUIC processes that packet accordingly.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If the Destination Connection ID is zero length and the addressing information in the packet matches the addressing information the endpoint uses to identify a connection with a zero-length connection ID, QUIC processes the packet as part of that connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints can send a Stateless Reset (Section 10.3) for any packets that cannot be attributed to an existing connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Packets that are matched to an existing connection are discarded if the packets are inconsistent with the state of that connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Invalid packets that lack strong integrity protection, such as Initial, Retry, or Version Negotiation, MAY be discarded.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Valid packets sent to clients always include a Destination Connection ID that matches a value the client selects.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Clients that choose to receive zero-length connection IDs can use the local address and port to identify a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Due to packet reordering or loss, a client might receive packets for a connection that are encrypted with a key it has not yet computed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If a server receives a packet that indicates an unsupported version and if the packet is large enough to initiate a new connection for any supported version, the server SHOULD send a Version Negotiation packet as described in Section 6.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server MAY limit the number of packets to which it responds with a Version Negotiation packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The first packet for an unsupported version can use different semantics and encodings for any version-specific field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] In particular, different packet protection keys might be used for different versions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Servers that do not support a particular version are unlikely to be able to decrypt the payload of the packet or properly interpret the result.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Packets with a supported version, or no Version field, are matched to a connection using the connection ID or -- for packets with zero-length connection IDs -- the local address and port.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If the packet is an Initial packet fully conforming with the specification, the server proceeds with the handshake (Section 7).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If the packet is a 0-RTT packet, the server MAY buffer a limited number of these packets in anticipation of a late-arriving Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server deployment could load-balance among servers using only source and destination IP addresses and ports.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Changes to the client's IP address or port could result in packets being forwarded to the wrong server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server in a deployment that does not implement a solution to maintain connection continuity when the client address changes SHOULD indicate that migration is not supported by using the disable_active_migration transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This document does not define an API for QUIC; it instead defines a set of functions for QUIC connections that application protocols can rely upon.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An application protocol can assume that an implementation of QUIC provides an interface that includes the operations described in this section.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Version negotiation allows a server to indicate that it does not support the version the client used.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The size of the first packet sent by a client will determine whether a server sends a Version Negotiation packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Clients that support multiple QUIC versions SHOULD ensure that the first UDP datagram they send is sized to the largest of the minimum datagram sizes from all versions they support, using PADDING frames (Section 19.1) as necessary.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This ensures that the server responds if there is a mutually supported version.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If the version selected by the client is not acceptable to the server, the server responds with a Version Negotiation packet; see Section 17.2.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This includes a list of versions that the server will accept.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This system allows a server to process packets with unsupported versions without retaining state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server MAY limit the number of Version Negotiation packets it sends.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Version Negotiation packets are designed to allow for functionality to be defined in the future that allows QUIC to negotiate the version of QUIC to use for a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A client that supports only this version of QUIC MUST abandon the current connection attempt if it receives a Version Negotiation packet, with the following two exceptions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A client MUST discard any Version Negotiation packet if it has received and successfully processed any other packet, including an earlier Version Negotiation packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] How to perform version negotiation is left as future work defined by future Standards Track specifications.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] For a server to use a new version in the future, clients need to correctly handle unsupported versions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints MAY add reserved versions to any field where unknown or unsupported versions are ignored to test that a peer correctly ignores the value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] For instance, an endpoint could include a reserved version in a Version Negotiation packet; see Section 17.2.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] QUIC relies on a combined cryptographic and transport handshake to minimize connection establishment latency.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] QUIC uses the CRYPTO frame (Section 19.6) to transmit the cryptographic handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] QUIC provides reliable, ordered delivery of the cryptographic handshake data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] QUIC packet protection is used to encrypt as much of the handshake protocol as possible.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The CRYPTO frame can be sent in different packet number spaces (Section 12.3).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Figure 4 shows a simplified handshake and the exchange of packets and frames that are used to advance the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Exchange of application data during the handshake is enabled where possible, shown with an asterisk ("*").
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints can use packets sent during the handshake to test for Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN) support; see Section 13.4.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints MUST explicitly negotiate an application protocol.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Details of how TLS is integrated with QUIC are provided in [QUIC-TLS], but some examples are provided here.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Once any address validation exchanges are complete, the cryptographic handshake is used to agree on cryptographic keys.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Figure 5 provides an overview of the 1-RTT handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Each line shows a QUIC packet with the packet type and packet number shown first, followed by the frames that are typically contained in those packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Multiple QUIC packets -- even of different packet types -- can be coalesced into a single UDP datagram; see Section 12.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] As a result, this handshake could consist of as few as four UDP datagrams, or any number more (subject to limits inherent to the protocol, such as congestion control and anti-amplification).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Figure 6 shows an example of a connection with a 0-RTT handshake and a single packet of 0-RTT data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A connection ID is used to ensure consistent routing of packets, as described in Section 5.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] During the handshake, packets with the long header (Section 17.2) are used to establish the connection IDs used by both endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Each endpoint uses the Source Connection ID field to specify the connection ID that is used in the Destination Connection ID field of packets being sent to them.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] When an Initial packet is sent by a client that has not previously received an Initial or Retry packet from the server, the client populates the Destination Connection ID field with an unpredictable value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This Destination Connection ID MUST be at least 8 bytes in length.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The Destination Connection ID field from the first Initial packet sent by a client is used to determine packet protection keys for Initial packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Upon first receiving an Initial or Retry packet from the server, the client uses the Source Connection ID supplied by the server as the Destination Connection ID for subsequent packets, including any 0-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] This means that a client might have to change the connection ID it sets in the Destination Connection ID field twice during connection establishment: once in response to a Retry packet and once in response to an Initial packet from the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A client MUST change the Destination Connection ID it uses for sending packets in response to only the first received Initial or Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server MUST set the Destination Connection ID it uses for sending packets based on the first received Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Any further changes to the Destination Connection ID are only permitted if the values are taken from NEW_CONNECTION_ID frames; if subsequent Initial packets include a different Source Connection ID, they MUST be discarded.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The choice each endpoint makes about connection IDs during the handshake is authenticated by including all values in transport parameters; see Section 7.4.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Each endpoint includes the value of the Source Connection ID field from the first Initial packet it sent in the initial_source_connection_id transport parameter; see Section 18.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server includes the Destination Connection ID field from the first Initial packet it received from the client in the original_destination_connection_id transport parameter; if the server sent a Retry packet, this refers to the first Initial packet received before sending the Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The values provided by a peer for these transport parameters MUST match the values that an endpoint used in the Destination and Source Connection ID fields of Initial packets that it sent (and received, for servers).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints MUST validate that received transport parameters match received connection ID values.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Figure 7 shows the connection IDs (with DCID=Destination Connection ID, SCID=Source Connection ID) that are used in a complete handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] When the handshake does not include a Retry (Figure 7), the server sets original_destination_connection_id to `S1` (note that this value is chosen by the client) and initial_source_connection_id to `S3`.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] During connection establishment, both endpoints make authenticated declarations of their transport parameters.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Transport parameters are declarations that are made unilaterally by each endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] QUIC includes the encoded transport parameters in the cryptographic handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Once the handshake completes, the transport parameters declared by the peer are available.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint MUST NOT send a parameter more than once in a given transport parameters extension.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] ALPN (see [ALPN]) allows clients to offer multiple application protocols during connection establishment.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The transport parameters that a client includes during the handshake apply to all application protocols that the client offers.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Application protocols can recommend values for transport parameters, such as the initial flow control limits.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Using 0-RTT depends on both client and server using protocol parameters that were negotiated from a previous connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] To enable 0-RTT, endpoints store the values of the server transport parameters with any session tickets it receives on the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints also store any information required by the application protocol or cryptographic handshake; see Section 4.6 of [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Remembered transport parameters apply to the new connection until the handshake completes and the client starts sending 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Once the handshake completes, the client uses the transport parameters established in the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The definition of a new transport parameter (Section 7.4.2) MUST specify whether storing the transport parameter for 0-RTT is mandatory, optional, or prohibited.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A client MUST NOT use remembered values for the following parameters: ack_delay_exponent, max_ack_delay, initial_source_connection_id, original_destination_connection_id, preferred_address, retry_source_connection_id, and stateless_reset_token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A client that attempts to send 0-RTT data MUST remember all other transport parameters used by the server that it is able to process.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The server can remember these transport parameters or can store an integrity-protected copy of the values in the ticket and recover the information when accepting 0-RTT data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If 0-RTT data is accepted by the server, the server MUST NOT reduce any limits or alter any values that might be violated by the client with its 0-RTT data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Omitting or setting a zero value for certain transport parameters can result in 0-RTT data being enabled but not usable.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The applicable subset of transport parameters that permit the sending of application data SHOULD be set to non-zero values for 0-RTT.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server might provide larger initial stream flow control limits for streams than the remembered values that a client applies when sending 0-RTT.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A server MAY store and recover the previously sent values of the max_idle_timeout, max_udp_payload_size, and disable_active_migration parameters and reject 0-RTT if it selects smaller values.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Lowering the values of these parameters while also accepting 0-RTT data could degrade the performance of the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] When sending frames in 0-RTT packets, a client MUST only use remembered transport parameters; importantly, it MUST NOT use updated values that it learns from the server's updated transport parameters or from frames received in 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Updated values of transport parameters from the handshake apply only to 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] For instance, flow control limits from remembered transport parameters apply to all 0-RTT packets even if those values are increased by the handshake or by frames sent in 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] New transport parameters can be used to negotiate new protocol behavior.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] An endpoint MUST ignore transport parameters that it does not support.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] The absence of a transport parameter therefore disables any optional protocol feature that is negotiated using the parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A client that does not understand a transport parameter can discard it and attempt 0-RTT on subsequent connections.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] However, if the client adds support for a discarded transport parameter, it risks violating the constraints that the transport parameter establishes if it attempts 0-RTT.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] New transport parameters can avoid this problem by setting a default of the most conservative value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Implementations need to maintain a buffer of CRYPTO data received out of order.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Implementations MUST support buffering at least 4096 bytes of data received in out-of-order CRYPTO frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Endpoints MAY choose to allow more data to be buffered during the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] A larger limit during the handshake could allow for larger keys or credentials to be exchanged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Being unable to buffer CRYPTO frames during the handshake can lead to a connection failure.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] If an endpoint's buffer is exceeded during the handshake, it can expand its buffer temporarily to complete the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p02] Once the handshake completes, if an endpoint is unable to buffer all data in a CRYPTO frame, it MAY discard that CRYPTO frame and all CRYPTO frames received in the future, or it MAY close the connection with a CRYPTO_BUFFER_EXCEEDED error code.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Address validation ensures that an endpoint cannot be used for a traffic amplification attack.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In such an attack, a packet is sent to a server with spoofed source address information that identifies a victim.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The primary defense against amplification attacks is verifying that a peer is able to receive packets at the transport address that it claims.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Therefore, after receiving packets from an address that is not yet validated, an endpoint MUST limit the amount of data it sends to the unvalidated address to three times the amount of data received from that address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Connection establishment implicitly provides address validation for both endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In particular, receipt of a packet protected with Handshake keys confirms that the peer successfully processed an Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For the client, the value of the Destination Connection ID field in its first Initial packet allows it to validate the server address as a part of successfully processing any packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Initial packets from the server are protected with keys that are derived from this value (see Section 5.2 of [QUIC-TLS]).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Prior to validating the client address, servers MUST NOT send more than three times as many bytes as the number of bytes they have received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This limits the magnitude of any amplification attack that can be mounted using spoofed source addresses.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For the purposes of avoiding amplification prior to address validation, servers MUST count all of the payload bytes received in datagrams that are uniquely attributed to a single connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Clients MUST ensure that UDP datagrams containing Initial packets have UDP payloads of at least 1200 bytes, adding PADDING frames as necessary.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Loss of an Initial or Handshake packet from the server can cause a deadlock if the client does not send additional Initial or Handshake packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A deadlock could occur when the server reaches its anti-amplification limit and the client has received acknowledgments for all the data it has sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In this case, when the client has no reason to send additional packets, the server will be unable to send more data because it has not validated the client's address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] To prevent this deadlock, clients MUST send a packet on a Probe Timeout (PTO); see Section 6.2 of [QUIC-RECOVERY].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A server might wish to validate the client address before starting the cryptographic handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] QUIC uses a token in the Initial packet to provide address validation prior to completing the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In addition to sending limits imposed prior to address validation, servers are also constrained in what they can send by the limits set by the congestion controller.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A token sent in a NEW_TOKEN frame or a Retry packet MUST be constructed in a way that allows the server to identify how it was provided to a client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Upon receiving the client's Initial packet, the server can request address validation by sending a Retry packet (Section 17.2.5) containing a token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A server can also use a Retry packet to defer the state and processing costs of connection establishment.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Requiring the server to provide a different connection ID, along with the original_destination_connection_id transport parameter defined in Section 18.2, forces the server to demonstrate that it, or an entity it cooperates with, received the original Initial packet from the client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Providing a different connection ID also grants a server some control over how subsequent packets are routed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If a server receives a client Initial that contains an invalid Retry token but is otherwise valid, it knows the client will not accept another Retry token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The server can discard such a packet and allow the client to time out to detect handshake failure, but that could impose a significant latency penalty on the client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Instead, the server SHOULD immediately close (Section 10.2) the connection with an INVALID_TOKEN error.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A server MAY provide clients with an address validation token during one connection that can be used on a subsequent connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The server uses the NEW_TOKEN frame (Section 19.7) to provide the client with an address validation token that can be used to validate future connections.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In a future connection, the client includes this token in Initial packets to provide address validation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The client MUST include the token in all Initial packets it sends, unless a Retry replaces the token with a newer one.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The client MUST NOT use the token provided in a Retry for future connections.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Unlike the token that is created for a Retry packet, which is used immediately, the token sent in the NEW_TOKEN frame can be used after some period of time has passed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Thus, a token SHOULD have an expiration time, which could be either an explicit expiration time or an issued timestamp that can be used to dynamically calculate the expiration time.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A token issued with NEW_TOKEN MUST NOT include information that would allow values to be linked by an observer to the connection on which it was issued.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For example, it cannot include the previous connection ID or addressing information, unless the values are encrypted.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A server MUST ensure that every NEW_TOKEN frame it sends is unique across all clients, with the exception of those sent to repair losses of previously sent NEW_TOKEN frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A token received in a NEW_TOKEN frame is applicable to any server that the connection is considered authoritative for (e.g., server names included in the certificate).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When connecting to a server for which the client retains an applicable and unused token, it SHOULD include that token in the Token field of its Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Including a token might allow the server to validate the client address without an additional round trip.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A client MUST NOT include a token that is not applicable to the server that it is connecting to, unless the client has the knowledge that the server that issued the token and the server the client is connecting to are jointly managing the tokens.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A token allows a server to correlate activity between the connection where the token was issued and any connection where it is used.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Clients that want to break continuity of identity with a server can discard tokens provided using the NEW_TOKEN frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A client SHOULD NOT reuse a token from a NEW_TOKEN frame for different connection attempts.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Clients might receive multiple tokens on a single connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Aside from preventing linkability, any token can be used in any connection attempt.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Servers can send additional tokens to either enable address validation for multiple connection attempts or replace older tokens that might become invalid.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For a client, this ambiguity means that sending the most recent unused token is most likely to be effective.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When a server receives an Initial packet with an address validation token, it MUST attempt to validate the token, unless it has already completed address validation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the token is invalid, then the server SHOULD proceed as if the client did not have a validated address, including potentially sending a Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Tokens provided with NEW_TOKEN frames and Retry packets can be distinguished by servers (see Section 8.1.1), and the latter can be validated more strictly.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In a stateless design, a server can use encrypted and authenticated tokens to pass information to clients that the server can later recover and use to validate a client address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Tokens are not integrated into the cryptographic handshake, and so they are not authenticated.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For instance, a client might be able to reuse a token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Clients MAY use tokens obtained on one connection for any connection attempt using the same version.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An address validation token MUST be difficult to guess.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A token-based scheme allows the server to offload any state associated with validation to the client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For this design to work, the token MUST be covered by integrity protection against modification or falsification by clients.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Without integrity protection, malicious clients could generate or guess values for tokens that would be accepted by the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] There is no need for a single well-defined format for the token because the server that generates the token also consumes it.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Tokens sent in NEW_TOKEN frames MUST include information that allows the server to verify that the client IP address has not changed from when the token was issued.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Servers can use tokens from NEW_TOKEN frames in deciding not to send a Retry packet, even if the client address has changed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the client IP address has changed, the server MUST adhere to the anti-amplification limit; see Section 8.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Attackers could replay tokens to use servers as amplifiers in DDoS attacks.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] To protect against such attacks, servers MUST ensure that replay of tokens is prevented or limited.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Servers SHOULD ensure that tokens sent in Retry packets are only accepted for a short time, as they are returned immediately by clients.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Tokens that are provided in NEW_TOKEN frames (Section 19.7) need to be valid for longer but SHOULD NOT be accepted multiple times.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Path validation is used by both peers during connection migration (see Section 9) to verify reachability after a change of address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Path validation tests that packets sent on a path to a peer are received by that peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Path validation does not validate that a peer can send in the return direction.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Acknowledgments cannot be used for return path validation because they contain insufficient entropy and might be spoofed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Path validation can be used at any time by either endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Path validation is not designed as a NAT traversal mechanism.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Though the mechanism described here might be effective for the creation of NAT bindings that support NAT traversal, the expectation is that one endpoint is able to receive packets without first having sent a packet on that path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MAY include other frames with the PATH_CHALLENGE and PATH_RESPONSE frames used for path validation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In particular, an endpoint can include PADDING frames with a PATH_CHALLENGE frame for Path Maximum Transmission Unit Discovery (PMTUD); see Section 14.2.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint uses a new connection ID for probes sent from a new local address; see Section 9.5.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When probing a new path, an endpoint can ensure that its peer has an unused connection ID available for responses.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint can choose to simultaneously probe multiple paths.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MAY send multiple PATH_CHALLENGE frames to guard against packet loss.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint SHOULD NOT probe a new path with packets containing a PATH_CHALLENGE frame more frequently than it would send an Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MUST expand datagrams that contain a PATH_CHALLENGE frame to at least the smallest allowed maximum datagram size of 1200 bytes, unless the anti-amplification limit for the path does not permit sending a datagram of this size.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When an endpoint is unable to expand the datagram size to 1200 bytes due to the anti-amplification limit, the path MTU will not be validated.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] To ensure that the path MTU is large enough, the endpoint MUST perform a second path validation by sending a PATH_CHALLENGE frame in a datagram of at least 1200 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] On receiving a PATH_CHALLENGE frame, an endpoint MUST respond by echoing the data contained in the PATH_CHALLENGE frame in a PATH_RESPONSE frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A PATH_RESPONSE frame MUST be sent on the network path where the PATH_CHALLENGE frame was received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This ensures that path validation by a peer only succeeds if the path is functional in both directions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MUST expand datagrams that contain a PATH_RESPONSE frame to at least the smallest allowed maximum datagram size of 1200 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This verifies that the path is able to carry datagrams of this size in both directions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] However, an endpoint MUST NOT expand the datagram containing the PATH_RESPONSE if the resulting data exceeds the anti-amplification limit.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MUST NOT send more than one PATH_RESPONSE frame in response to one PATH_CHALLENGE frame; see Section 13.3.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Path validation succeeds when a PATH_RESPONSE frame is received that contains the data that was sent in a previous PATH_CHALLENGE frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If an endpoint sends a PATH_CHALLENGE frame in a datagram that is not expanded to at least 1200 bytes and if the response to it validates the peer address, the path is validated but not the path MTU.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] As a result, the endpoint can now send more than three times the amount of data that has been received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Endpoints SHOULD abandon path validation based on a timer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When setting this timer, implementations are cautioned that the new path could have a longer round-trip time than the original.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When an endpoint abandons path validation, it determines that the path is unusable.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This does not necessarily imply a failure of the connection -- endpoints can continue sending packets over other paths as appropriate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If no paths are available, an endpoint can wait for a new path to become available or close the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A path validation might be abandoned for other reasons besides failure.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The use of a connection ID allows connections to survive changes to endpoint addresses (IP address and port), such as those caused by an endpoint migrating to a new network.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The design of QUIC relies on endpoints retaining a stable address for the duration of the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the peer violates this requirement, the endpoint MUST either drop the incoming packets on that path without generating a Stateless Reset or proceed with path validation and allow the peer to migrate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Not all changes of peer address are intentional, or active, migrations.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The peer could experience NAT rebinding: a change of address due to a middlebox, usually a NAT, allocating a new outgoing port or even a new outgoing IP address for a flow.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When an endpoint has no validated path on which to send packets, it MAY discard connection state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This document limits migration of connections to new client addresses, except as described in Section 9.6.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Clients are responsible for initiating all migrations.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Servers do not send non-probing packets (see Section 9.1) toward a client address until they see a non-probing packet from that address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MAY probe for peer reachability from a new local address using path validation (Section 8.2) prior to migrating the connection to the new local address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Failure of path validation simply means that the new path is not usable for this connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] PATH_CHALLENGE, PATH_RESPONSE, NEW_CONNECTION_ID, and PADDING frames are "probing frames", and all other frames are "non-probing frames".
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Each endpoint validates its peer's address during connection establishment.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Therefore, a migrating endpoint can send to its peer knowing that the peer is willing to receive at the peer's current address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] To establish reachability on the new path, an endpoint initiates path validation (Section 8.2) on the new path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] When migrating, the new path might not support the endpoint's current sending rate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The new path might not have the same ECN capability.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the recipient permits the migration, it MUST send subsequent packets to the new peer address and MUST initiate path validation (Section 8.2) to verify the peer's ownership of the address if validation is not already underway.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint only changes the address to which it sends packets in response to the highest-numbered non-probing packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MAY send data to an unvalidated peer address, but it MUST protect against potential attacks as described in Sections 9.3.1 and 9.3.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint MAY skip validation of a peer address if that address has been seen recently.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] It is possible that a peer is spoofing its source address to cause an endpoint to send excessive amounts of data to an unwilling host.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] As described in Section 9.3, an endpoint is required to validate a peer's new address to confirm the peer's possession of the new address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Until a peer's address is deemed valid, an endpoint limits the amount of data it sends to that address; see Section 8.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An on-path attacker could cause a spurious connection migration by copying and forwarding a packet with a spoofed address such that it arrives before the original packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The packet with the spoofed address will be seen to come from a migrating connection, and the original packet will be seen as a duplicate and dropped.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] To protect the connection from failing due to such a spurious migration, an endpoint MUST revert to using the last validated peer address when validation of a new peer address fails.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Additionally, receipt of packets with higher packet numbers from the legitimate peer address will trigger another connection migration.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If an endpoint has no state about the last validated peer address, it MUST close the connection silently by discarding all connection state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This results in new packets on the connection being handled generically.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An off-path attacker that can observe packets might forward copies of genuine packets to endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the copied packet arrives before the genuine packet, this will appear as a NAT rebinding.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Any genuine packet will be discarded as a duplicate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the attacker is able to continue forwarding packets, it might be able to cause migration to a path via the attacker.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This style of attack relies on the attacker using a path that has approximately the same characteristics as the direct path between endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A non-probing packet received on the original path that increases the maximum received packet number will cause the endpoint to move back to that path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Eliciting packets on this path increases the likelihood that the attack is unsuccessful.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In response to an apparent migration, endpoints MUST validate the previously active path using a PATH_CHALLENGE frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This induces the sending of new packets on that path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint that receives a PATH_CHALLENGE on an active path SHOULD send a non-probing packet in response.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the non-probing packet arrives before any copy made by an attacker, this results in the connection being migrated back to the original path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This defense is imperfect, but this is not considered a serious problem.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint could also use heuristics to improve detection of this style of attack.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For instance, NAT rebinding is improbable if packets were recently received on the old path; similarly, rebinding is rare on IPv6 paths.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Endpoints can also look for duplicated packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The capacity available on the new path might not be the same as the old path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] On confirming a peer's ownership of its new address, an endpoint MUST immediately reset the congestion controller and round-trip time estimator for the new path to initial values (see Appendices A.3 and B.3 of [QUIC-RECOVERY]) unless the only change in the peer's address is its port number.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Because port-only changes are commonly the result of NAT rebinding or other middlebox activity, the endpoint MAY instead retain its congestion control state and round-trip estimate in those cases instead of reverting to initial values.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] In cases where congestion control state retained from an old path is used on a new path with substantially different characteristics, a sender could transmit too aggressively until the congestion controller and the RTT estimator have adapted.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] There could be apparent reordering at the receiver when an endpoint sends data and probes from/to multiple addresses during the migration period, since the two resulting paths could have different round-trip times.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] While multiple paths might be used during connection migration, a single congestion control context and a single loss recovery context (as described in [QUIC-RECOVERY]) could be adequate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A sender can make exceptions for probe packets so that their loss detection is independent and does not unduly cause the congestion controller to reduce its sending rate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint might set a separate timer when a PATH_CHALLENGE is sent, which is canceled if the corresponding PATH_RESPONSE is received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the timer fires before the PATH_RESPONSE is received, the endpoint might send a new PATH_CHALLENGE and restart the timer for a longer period of time.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Using a stable connection ID on multiple network paths would allow a passive observer to correlate activity between those paths.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint that moves between networks might not wish to have their activity correlated by any entity other than their peer, so different connection IDs are used when sending from different local addresses, as discussed in Section 5.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Similarly, an endpoint MUST NOT reuse a connection ID when sending to more than one destination address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] These requirements regarding connection ID reuse apply only to the sending of packets, as unintentional changes in path without a change in connection ID are possible.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For example, after a period of network inactivity, NAT rebinding might cause packets to be sent on a new path when the client resumes sending.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Using different connection IDs for packets sent in both directions on each new network path eliminates the use of the connection ID for linking packets from the same connection across different network paths.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Header protection ensures that packet numbers cannot be used to correlate activity.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint SHOULD NOT initiate migration with a peer that has requested a zero-length connection ID, because traffic over the new path might be trivially linkable to traffic over the old one.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If the server is able to associate packets with a zero-length connection ID to the right connection, it means that the server is using other information to demultiplex packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] For example, a server might provide a unique address to every client -- for instance, using HTTP alternative services [ALTSVC].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A client might wish to reduce linkability by switching to a new connection ID, source UDP port, or IP address (see [RFC8981]) when sending traffic after a period of inactivity.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Changing the address from which it sends packets at the same time might cause the server to detect a connection migration.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This ensures that the mechanisms that support migration are exercised even for clients that do not experience NAT rebindings or genuine migrations.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] An endpoint that exhausts available connection IDs cannot probe new paths or initiate migration, nor can it respond to probes or attempts by its peer to migrate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] To ensure that migration is possible and packets sent on different paths cannot be correlated, endpoints SHOULD provide new connection IDs before peers migrate; see Section 5.1.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] QUIC allows servers to accept connections on one IP address and attempt to transfer these connections to a more preferred address shortly after the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] This is particularly useful when clients initially connect to an address shared by multiple servers but would prefer to use a unicast address to ensure connection stability.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Migrating a connection to a new server address mid-connection is not supported by the version of QUIC specified in this document.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Once the handshake is confirmed, the client SHOULD select one of the two addresses provided by the server and initiate path validation (see Section 8.2).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] As soon as path validation succeeds, the client SHOULD begin sending all future packets to the new server address using the new connection ID and discontinue use of the old server address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A server might receive a packet addressed to its preferred IP address at any time after it accepts a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If this packet contains a PATH_CHALLENGE frame, the server sends a packet containing a PATH_RESPONSE frame as per Section 8.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The server MUST probe on the path toward the client from its preferred address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Once the server has completed its path validation and has received a non-probing packet with a new largest packet number on its preferred address, the server begins sending non-probing packets to the client exclusively from its preferred IP address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The server SHOULD drop newer packets for this connection that are received on the old IP address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The addresses that a server provides in the preferred_address transport parameter are only valid for the connection in which they are provided.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] A client might need to perform a connection migration before it has migrated to the server's preferred address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If path validation of the server's preferred address succeeds, the client MUST abandon validation of the original address and migrate to using the server's preferred address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] If packets received at the server's preferred address have a different source address than observed from the client during the handshake, the server MUST protect against potential attacks as described in Sections 9.3.1 and 9.3.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] The connection ID provided in the preferred_address transport parameter is not specific to the addresses that are provided.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] [RFC6437] suggests deriving values using a pseudorandom function to generate flow labels.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p03] Including the Destination Connection ID field in addition to source and destination addresses when generating flow labels ensures that changes are synchronized with changes in other observable identifiers.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Each endpoint advertises a max_idle_timeout, but the effective value at an endpoint is computed as the minimum of the two advertised values (or the sole advertised value, if only one endpoint advertises a non-zero value).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint restarts its idle timer when a packet from its peer is received and processed successfully.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint also restarts its idle timer when sending an ack-eliciting packet if no other ack-eliciting packets have been sent since last receiving and processing a packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] To avoid excessively small idle timeout periods, endpoints MUST increase the idle timeout period to be at least three times the current Probe Timeout (PTO).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint can send a PING or another ack-eliciting frame to test the connection for liveness if the peer could time out soon, such as within a PTO; see Section 6.2 of [QUIC-RECOVERY].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This is especially useful if any available application data cannot be safely retried.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An implementation of QUIC might provide applications with an option to defer an idle timeout.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This facility could be used when the application wishes to avoid losing state that has been associated with an open connection but does not expect to exchange application data for some time.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] With this option, an endpoint could send a PING frame (Section 19.2) periodically, which will cause the peer to restart its idle timeout period.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Sending a packet containing a PING frame restarts the idle timeout for this endpoint also if this is the first ack-eliciting packet sent since receiving a packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Application protocols that use QUIC SHOULD provide guidance on when deferring an idle timeout is appropriate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A connection will time out if no packets are sent or received for a period longer than the time negotiated using the max_idle_timeout transport parameter; see Section 10.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] However, state in middleboxes might time out earlier than that.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint sends a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame (Section 19.19) to terminate the connection immediately.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] After sending a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame, an endpoint immediately enters the closing state; see Section 10.2.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An immediate close can be used after an application protocol has arranged to close a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This might be after the application protocol negotiates a graceful shutdown.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The application protocol can exchange messages that are needed for both application endpoints to agree that the connection can be closed, after which the application requests that QUIC close the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The closing and draining connection states exist to ensure that connections close cleanly and that delayed or reordered packets are properly discarded.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Disposing of connection state prior to exiting the closing or draining state could result in an endpoint generating a Stateless Reset unnecessarily when it receives a late-arriving packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Endpoints that have some alternative means to ensure that late-arriving packets do not induce a response, such as those that are able to close the UDP socket, MAY end these states earlier to allow for faster resource recovery.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Once its closing or draining state ends, an endpoint SHOULD discard all connection state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] In the closing state, an endpoint retains only enough information to generate a packet containing a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame and to identify packets as belonging to the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint SHOULD limit the rate at which it generates packets in the closing state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint's selected connection ID and the QUIC version are sufficient information to identify packets for a closing connection; the endpoint MAY discard all other connection state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that is closing is not required to process any received frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MAY drop packet protection keys when entering the closing state and send a packet containing a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame in response to any UDP datagram that is received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] However, an endpoint that discards packet protection keys cannot identify and discard invalid packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] To avoid being used for an amplification attack, such endpoints MUST limit the cumulative size of packets it sends to three times the cumulative size of the packets that are received and attributed to the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] While in the closing state, an endpoint could receive packets from a new source address, possibly indicating a connection migration; see Section 9.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint is not expected to handle key updates when it is closing (Section 6 of [QUIC-TLS]).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The draining state is entered once an endpoint receives a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame, which indicates that its peer is closing or draining.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] While otherwise identical to the closing state, an endpoint in the draining state MUST NOT send any packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that receives a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame MAY send a single packet containing a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame before entering the draining state, using a NO_ERROR code if appropriate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MUST NOT send further packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MAY enter the draining state from the closing state if it receives a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame, which indicates that the peer is also closing or draining.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] In this case, the draining state ends when the closing state would have ended.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] When sending a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame, the goal is to ensure that the peer will process the frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Generally, this means sending the frame in a packet with the highest level of packet protection to avoid the packet being discarded.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] After the handshake is confirmed (see Section 4.1.2 of [QUIC-TLS]), an endpoint MUST send any CONNECTION_CLOSE frames in a 1-RTT packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] However, prior to confirming the handshake, it is possible that more advanced packet protection keys are not available to the peer, so another CONNECTION_CLOSE frame MAY be sent in a packet that uses a lower packet protection level.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Sending a CONNECTION_CLOSE of type 0x1d in an Initial or Handshake packet could expose application state or be used to alter application state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A CONNECTION_CLOSE of type 0x1d MUST be replaced by a CONNECTION_CLOSE of type 0x1c when sending the frame in Initial or Handshake packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Otherwise, information about the application state might be revealed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint can send a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame in an Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This might be in response to unauthenticated information received in Initial or Handshake packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Such an immediate close might expose legitimate connections to a denial of service.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] QUIC does not include defensive measures for on-path attacks during the handshake; see Section 21.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] However, at the cost of reducing feedback about errors for legitimate peers, some forms of denial of service can be made more difficult for an attacker if endpoints discard illegal packets rather than terminating a connection with CONNECTION_CLOSE.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that has not established state, such as a server that detects an error in an Initial packet, does not enter the closing state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A stateless reset is provided as an option of last resort for an endpoint that does not have access to the state of a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A crash or outage might result in peers continuing to send data to an endpoint that is unable to properly continue the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A stateless reset is not appropriate for indicating errors in active connections.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] To support this process, an endpoint issues a stateless reset token, which is a 16-byte value that is hard to guess.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A stateless reset token is specific to a connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint issues a stateless reset token by including the value in the Stateless Reset Token field of a NEW_CONNECTION_ID frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Servers can also issue a stateless_reset_token transport parameter during the handshake that applies to the connection ID that it selected during the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] These exchanges are protected by encryption, so only client and server know their value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A Stateless Reset uses an entire UDP datagram, starting with the first two bits of the packet header.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The remainder of the first byte and an arbitrary number of bytes following it are set to values that SHOULD be indistinguishable from random.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] To entities other than its intended recipient, a Stateless Reset will appear to be a packet with a short header.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The resulting minimum size of 21 bytes does not guarantee that a Stateless Reset is difficult to distinguish from other packets if the recipient requires the use of a connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] To achieve that end, the endpoint SHOULD ensure that all packets it sends are at least 22 bytes longer than the minimum connection ID length that it requests the peer to include in its packets, adding PADDING frames as necessary.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This ensures that any Stateless Reset sent by the peer is indistinguishable from a valid packet sent to the endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] These values assume that the stateless reset token is the same length as the minimum expansion of the packet protection AEAD.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MUST NOT send a Stateless Reset that is three times or more larger than the packet it receives to avoid being used for amplification.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Endpoints MUST discard packets that are too small to be valid QUIC packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Endpoints MUST send Stateless Resets formatted as a packet with a short header.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MAY send a Stateless Reset in response to a packet with a long header.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Sending a Stateless Reset is not effective prior to the stateless reset token being available to a peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] In this QUIC version, packets with a long header are only used during connection establishment.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint cannot determine the Source Connection ID from a packet with a short header; therefore, it cannot set the Destination Connection ID in the Stateless Reset.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The Destination Connection ID will therefore differ from the value used in previous packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This stateless reset design is specific to QUIC version 1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that supports multiple versions of QUIC needs to generate a Stateless Reset that will be accepted by peers that support any version that the endpoint might support (or might have supported prior to losing state).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint detects a potential Stateless Reset using the trailing 16 bytes of the UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint remembers all stateless reset tokens associated with the connection IDs and remote addresses for datagrams it has recently sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This includes Stateless Reset Token field values from NEW_CONNECTION_ID frames and the server's transport parameters but excludes stateless reset tokens associated with connection IDs that are either unused or retired.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This comparison can be performed for every inbound datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Endpoints MAY skip this check if any packet from a datagram is successfully processed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] When comparing a datagram to stateless reset token values, endpoints MUST perform the comparison without leaking information about the value of the token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] For example, performing this comparison in constant time protects the value of individual stateless reset tokens from information leakage through timing side channels.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The stateless reset token MUST be difficult to guess.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] In order to create a stateless reset token, an endpoint could randomly generate [RANDOM] a secret for every connection that it creates.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] However, this presents a coordination problem when there are multiple instances in a cluster or a storage problem for an endpoint that might lose state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A single static key can be used across all connections to the same endpoint by generating the proof using a pseudorandom function that takes a static key and the connection ID chosen by the endpoint (see Section 5.1) as input.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint could use HMAC [RFC2104] (for example, HMAC(static_key, connection_id)) or the HMAC-based Key Derivation Function (HKDF) [RFC5869] (for example, using the static key as input keying material, with the connection ID as salt).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that loses state can use the same method to generate a valid stateless reset token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This design relies on the peer always sending a connection ID in its packets so that the endpoint can use the connection ID from a packet to reset the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that uses this design MUST either use the same connection ID length for all connections or encode the length of the connection ID such that it can be recovered without state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Revealing the stateless reset token allows any entity to terminate the connection, so a value can only be used once.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This method for choosing the stateless reset token means that the combination of connection ID and static key MUST NOT be used for another connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A denial-of-service attack is possible if the same connection ID is used by instances that share a static key or if an attacker can cause a packet to be routed to an instance that has no state but the same static key; see Section 21.11.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The same stateless reset token MUST NOT be used for multiple connection IDs.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The design of a Stateless Reset is such that without knowing the stateless reset token it is indistinguishable from a valid packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MUST ensure that every Stateless Reset that it sends is smaller than the packet that triggered it, unless it maintains state sufficient to prevent looping.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint can remember the number of Stateless Resets that it has sent and stop generating new Stateless Resets once a limit is reached.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A Stateless Reset that is smaller than 41 bytes might be identifiable as a Stateless Reset by an observer, depending upon the length of the peer's connection IDs.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that detects an error SHOULD signal the existence of that error to its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Both transport-level and application-level errors can affect an entire connection; see Section 11.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The most appropriate error code (Section 20) SHOULD be included in the frame that signals the error.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Where this specification identifies error conditions, it also identifies the error code that is used; though these are worded as requirements, different implementation strategies might lead to different errors being reported.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A stateless reset (Section 10.3) is not suitable for any error that can be signaled with a CONNECTION_CLOSE or RESET_STREAM frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Application-specific protocol errors are signaled using the CONNECTION_CLOSE frame with a frame type of 0x1d.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A CONNECTION_CLOSE frame could be sent in a packet that is lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint SHOULD be prepared to retransmit a packet containing a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame if it receives more packets on a terminated connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint that chooses not to retransmit packets containing a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame risks a peer missing the first such packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] As the AEAD for Initial packets does not provide strong authentication, an endpoint MAY discard an invalid Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Discarding an Initial packet is permitted even where this specification otherwise mandates a connection error.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint can only discard a packet if it does not process the frames in the packet or reverts the effects of any processing.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Resetting a stream without the involvement of the application protocol could cause the application protocol to enter an unrecoverable state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The semantics of the application error code carried in RESET_STREAM are defined by the application protocol.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Only the application protocol is able to cause a stream to be terminated.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] QUIC endpoints communicate by exchanging packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Packets have confidentiality and integrity protection; see Section 12.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This version of QUIC uses the long packet header during connection establishment; see Section 17.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Packets with the long header are Initial (Section 17.2.2), 0-RTT (Section 17.2.3), Handshake (Section 17.2.4), and Retry (Section 17.2.5).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] QUIC packets have different levels of cryptographic protection based on the type of packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Initial packets use an AEAD function, the keys for which are derived using a value that is visible on the wire.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Initial packets therefore do not have effective confidentiality protection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Initial protection exists to ensure that the sender of the packet is on the network path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Any entity that receives an Initial packet from a client can recover the keys that will allow them to both read the contents of the packet and generate Initial packets that will be successfully authenticated at either endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] All other packets are protected with keys derived from the cryptographic handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The cryptographic handshake ensures that only the communicating endpoints receive the corresponding keys for Handshake, 0-RTT, and 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The Packet Number field that appears in some packet types has alternative confidentiality protection that is applied as part of header protection; see Section 5.4 of [QUIC-TLS] for details.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Initial (Section 17.2.2), 0-RTT (Section 17.2.3), and Handshake (Section 17.2.4) packets contain a Length field that determines the end of the packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The length includes both the Packet Number and Payload fields, both of which are confidentiality protected and initially of unknown length.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Using the Length field, a sender can coalesce multiple QUIC packets into one UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This can reduce the number of UDP datagrams needed to complete the cryptographic handshake and start sending data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This can also be used to construct Path Maximum Transmission Unit (PMTU) probes; see Section 14.4.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Coalescing packets in order of increasing encryption levels (Initial, 0-RTT, Handshake, 1-RTT; see Section 4.1.4 of [QUIC-TLS]) makes it more likely that the receiver will be able to process all the packets in a single pass.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A packet with a short header does not include a length, so it can only be the last packet included in a UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Receivers MAY route based on the information in the first packet contained in a UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Senders MUST NOT coalesce QUIC packets with different connection IDs into a single UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Every QUIC packet that is coalesced into a single UDP datagram is separate and complete.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The receiver of coalesced QUIC packets MUST individually process each QUIC packet and separately acknowledge them, as if they were received as the payload of different UDP datagrams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Retry packets (Section 17.2.5), Version Negotiation packets (Section 17.2.1), and packets with a short header (Section 17.3) do not contain a Length field and so cannot be followed by other packets in the same UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The packet number is an integer in the range 0 to 262-1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This number is used in determining the cryptographic nonce for packet protection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Packet numbers are limited to this range because they need to be representable in whole in the Largest Acknowledged field of an ACK frame (Section 19.3).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Conceptually, a packet number space is the context in which a packet can be processed and acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Initial packets can only be sent with Initial packet protection keys and acknowledged in packets that are also Initial packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This enforces cryptographic separation between the data sent in the different packet number spaces.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Packet numbers in each space start at packet number 0.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A QUIC endpoint MUST NOT reuse a packet number within the same packet number space in one connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] A receiver MUST discard a newly unprotected packet unless it is certain that it has not processed another packet with the same packet number from the same packet number space.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Endpoints that track all individual packets for the purposes of detecting duplicates are at risk of accumulating excessive state.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The data required for detecting duplicates can be limited by maintaining a minimum packet number below which all packets are immediately dropped.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The payload of QUIC packets, after removing packet protection, consists of a sequence of complete frames, as shown in Figure 11.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The payload of a packet that contains frames MUST contain at least one frame, and MAY contain multiple frames and multiple frame types.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] An endpoint MUST treat receipt of a packet containing no frames as a connection error of type PROTOCOL_VIOLATION.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Table 3 lists and summarizes information about each frame type that is defined in this specification.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The format and semantics of each frame type are explained in more detail in Section 19.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The Frame Type in ACK, STREAM, MAX_STREAMS, STREAMS_BLOCKED, and CONNECTION_CLOSE frames is used to carry other frame-specific flags.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] For more details about these restrictions, see Section 12.5.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Note that all frames can appear in 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] All frames are idempotent in this version of QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] The Frame Type field uses a variable-length integer encoding (see Section 16), with one exception.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] To ensure simple and efficient implementations of frame parsing, a frame type MUST use the shortest possible encoding.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] For frame types defined in this document, this means a single-byte encoding, even though it is possible to encode these values as a two-, four-, or eight-byte variable-length integer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] For instance, though 0x4001 is a legitimate two-byte encoding for a variable-length integer with a value of 1, PING frames are always encoded as a single byte with the value 0x01.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] This rule applies to all current and future QUIC frame types.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Some frames are prohibited in different packet number spaces.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p04] Note that it is not possible to send the following frames in 0-RTT packets for various reasons: ACK, CRYPTO, HANDSHAKE_DONE, NEW_TOKEN, PATH_RESPONSE, and RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A sender can minimize per-packet bandwidth and computational costs by including as many frames as possible in each QUIC packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A sender MAY wait for a short period of time to collect multiple frames before sending a packet that is not maximally packed, to avoid sending out large numbers of small packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An implementation MAY use knowledge about application sending behavior or heuristics to determine whether and for how long to wait.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Stream multiplexing is achieved by interleaving STREAM frames from multiple streams into one or more QUIC packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] One of the benefits of QUIC is avoidance of head-of-line blocking across multiple streams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] When a packet loss occurs, only streams with data in that packet are blocked waiting for a retransmission to be received, while other streams can continue making progress.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Note that when data from multiple streams is included in a single QUIC packet, loss of that packet blocks all those streams from making progress.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A packet MUST NOT be acknowledged until packet protection has been successfully removed and all frames contained in the packet have been processed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint SHOULD treat receipt of an acknowledgment for a packet it did not send as a connection error of type PROTOCOL_VIOLATION, if it is able to detect the condition.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Endpoints acknowledge all packets they receive and process.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] However, only ack-eliciting packets cause an ACK frame to be sent within the maximum ack delay.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] When sending a packet for any reason, an endpoint SHOULD attempt to include an ACK frame if one has not been sent recently.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] In general, frequent feedback from a receiver improves loss and congestion response, but this has to be balanced against excessive load generated by a receiver that sends an ACK frame in response to every ack-eliciting packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] If it does, any excess accrues to the RTT estimate and could result in spurious or delayed retransmissions from the peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint MUST acknowledge all ack-eliciting Initial and Handshake packets immediately and all ack-eliciting 0-RTT and 1-RTT packets within its advertised max_ack_delay, with the following exception.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Prior to handshake confirmation, an endpoint might not have packet protection keys for decrypting Handshake, 0-RTT, or 1-RTT packets when they are received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint MUST NOT send a non-ack-eliciting packet in response to a non-ack-eliciting packet, even if there are packet gaps that precede the received packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This avoids an infinite feedback loop of acknowledgments, which could prevent the connection from ever becoming idle.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint that is only sending ACK frames will not receive acknowledgments from its peer unless those acknowledgments are included in packets with ack-eliciting frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint SHOULD send an ACK frame with other frames when there are new ack-eliciting packets to acknowledge.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint that is only sending non-ack-eliciting packets might choose to occasionally add an ack-eliciting frame to those packets to ensure that it receives an acknowledgment; see Section 13.2.4.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The algorithms in [QUIC-RECOVERY] are expected to be resilient to receivers that do not follow the guidance offered above.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver determines how frequently to send acknowledgments in response to ack-eliciting packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Endpoints rely on timely acknowledgment to detect loss; see Section 6 of [QUIC-RECOVERY].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Window-based congestion controllers, such as the one described in Section 7 of [QUIC-RECOVERY], rely on acknowledgments to manage their congestion window.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] On the other hand, reducing the frequency of packets that carry only acknowledgments reduces packet transmission and processing cost at both endpoints.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver SHOULD send an ACK frame after receiving at least two ack-eliciting packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This recommendation is general in nature and consistent with recommendations for TCP endpoint behavior [RFC5681].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] When an ACK frame is sent, one or more ranges of acknowledged packets are included.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ACK frames SHOULD always acknowledge the most recently received packets, and the more out of order the packets are, the more important it is to send an updated ACK frame quickly, to prevent the peer from declaring a packet as lost and spuriously retransmitting the frames it contains.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An ACK frame is expected to fit within a single QUIC packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver limits the number of ACK Ranges (Section 19.3.1) it remembers and sends in ACK frames, both to limit the size of ACK frames and to avoid resource exhaustion.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] After receiving acknowledgments for an ACK frame, the receiver SHOULD stop tracking those acknowledged ACK Ranges.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] It is possible that retaining many ACK Ranges could cause an ACK frame to become too large.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver can discard unacknowledged ACK Ranges to limit ACK frame size, at the cost of increased retransmissions from the sender.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This is necessary if an ACK frame would be too large to fit in a packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver MUST retain an ACK Range unless it can ensure that it will not subsequently accept packets with numbers in that range.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver SHOULD include an ACK Range containing the largest received packet number in every ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Section 13.2.4 describes an exemplary approach for determining what packets to acknowledge in each ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] When a packet containing an ACK frame is sent, the Largest Acknowledged field in that frame can be saved.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A receiver that sends only non-ack-eliciting packets, such as ACK frames, might not receive an acknowledgment for a long period of time.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This could cause the receiver to maintain state for a large number of ACK frames for a long period of time, and ACK frames it sends could be unnecessarily large.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] In cases without ACK frame loss, this algorithm allows for a minimum of 1 RTT of reordering.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] In cases with ACK frame loss and reordering, this approach does not guarantee that every acknowledgment is seen by the sender before it is no longer included in the ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Packets could be received out of order, and all subsequent ACK frames containing them could be lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint measures the delays intentionally introduced between the time the packet with the largest packet number is received and the time an acknowledgment is sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The endpoint encodes this acknowledgment delay in the ACK Delay field of an ACK frame; see Section 19.3.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A packet might be held in the OS kernel or elsewhere on the host before being processed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint MUST NOT include delays that it does not control when populating the ACK Delay field in an ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] When the measured acknowledgment delay is larger than its max_ack_delay, an endpoint SHOULD report the measured delay.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ACK frames MUST only be carried in a packet that has the same packet number space as the packet being acknowledged; see Section 12.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Packets that a client sends with 0-RTT packet protection MUST be acknowledged by the server in packets protected by 1-RTT keys.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This can mean that the client is unable to use these acknowledgments if the server cryptographic handshake messages are delayed or lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Packets containing PADDING frames are considered to be in flight for congestion control purposes [QUIC-RECOVERY].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Packets containing only PADDING frames therefore consume congestion window but do not generate acknowledgments that will open the congestion window.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC packets that are determined to be lost are not retransmitted whole.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The same applies to the frames that are contained within lost packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] New frames and packets are used to carry information that is determined to have been lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Even though a sender is encouraged to assemble frames containing up-to-date information every time it sends a packet, it is not forbidden to retransmit copies of frames from lost packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A sender that retransmits copies of frames needs to handle decreases in available payload size due to changes in packet number length, connection ID length, and path MTU.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A sender SHOULD avoid retransmitting information from packets once they are acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This includes packets that are acknowledged after being declared lost, which can happen in the presence of network reordering.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Doing so requires senders to retain information about packets after they are declared lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Upon detecting losses, a sender MUST take appropriate congestion control action.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC endpoints can use ECN [RFC3168] to detect and respond to network congestion.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ECN allows an endpoint to set an ECN-Capable Transport (ECT) codepoint in the ECN field of an IP packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A network node can then indicate congestion by setting the ECN-CE codepoint in the ECN field instead of dropping the packet [RFC8087].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The use of ECN requires the receiving endpoint to read the ECN field from an IP packet, which is not possible on all platforms.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Even if an endpoint does not set an ECT field in packets it sends, the endpoint MUST provide feedback about ECN markings it receives, if these are accessible.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] On receiving an IP packet with an ECT(0), ECT(1), or ECN-CE codepoint, an ECN-enabled endpoint accesses the ECN field and increases the corresponding ECT(0), ECT(1), or ECN-CE count.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Each packet number space maintains separate acknowledgment state and separate ECN counts.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ECN counts are only incremented when QUIC packets from the received IP packet are processed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] It is possible for faulty network devices to corrupt or erroneously drop packets that carry a non-zero ECN codepoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] If an endpoint has cause to expect that IP packets with an ECT codepoint might be dropped by a faulty network element, the endpoint could set an ECT codepoint for only the first ten outgoing packets on a path, or for a period of three PTOs (see Section 6.2 of [QUIC-RECOVERY]).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint thus attempts to use ECN and validates this for each new connection, when switching to a server's preferred address, and on active connection migration to a new path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Other methods of probing paths for ECN support are possible, as are different marking strategies.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Implementations MAY use other methods defined in RFCs; see [RFC8311].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Erroneous application of ECN-CE markings by the network can result in degraded connection performance.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint that receives an ACK frame with ECN counts therefore validates the counts before using them.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] It performs this validation by comparing newly received counts against those from the last successfully processed ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] If an ACK frame newly acknowledges a packet that the endpoint sent with either the ECT(0) or ECT(1) codepoint set, ECN validation fails if the corresponding ECN counts are not present in the ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ECN validation also fails if the sum of the increase in ECT(0) and ECN-CE counts is less than the number of newly acknowledged packets that were originally sent with an ECT(0) marking.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Similarly, ECN validation fails if the sum of the increases to ECT(1) and ECN-CE counts is less than the number of newly acknowledged packets sent with an ECT(1) marking.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint could miss acknowledgments for a packet when ACK frames are lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] It is therefore possible for the total increase in ECT(0), ECT(1), and ECN-CE counts to be greater than the number of packets that are newly acknowledged by an ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Validating ECN counts from reordered ACK frames can result in failure.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ECN validation can fail if the received total count for either ECT(0) or ECT(1) exceeds the total number of packets sent with each corresponding ECT codepoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] In particular, validation will fail when an endpoint receives a non-zero ECN count corresponding to an ECT codepoint that it never applied.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] If validation fails, then the endpoint MUST disable ECN.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Even if validation fails, an endpoint MAY revalidate ECN for the same path at any later time in the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Upon successful validation, an endpoint MAY continue to set an ECT codepoint in subsequent packets it sends, with the expectation that the path is ECN capable.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A UDP datagram can include one or more QUIC packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The datagram size refers to the total UDP payload size of a single UDP datagram carrying QUIC packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The maximum datagram size is defined as the largest size of UDP payload that can be sent across a network path using a single UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC assumes a minimum IP packet size of at least 1280 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This is the IPv6 minimum size [IPv6] and is also supported by most modern IPv4 networks.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Assuming the minimum IP header size of 40 bytes for IPv6 and 20 bytes for IPv4 and a UDP header size of 8 bytes, this results in a maximum datagram size of 1232 bytes for IPv6 and 1252 bytes for IPv4.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Enforcement of the max_udp_payload_size transport parameter (Section 18.2) might act as an additional limit on the maximum datagram size.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A sender can avoid exceeding this limit, once the value is known.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] UDP datagrams MUST NOT be fragmented at the IP layer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC sometimes requires datagrams to be no smaller than a certain size; see Section 8.1 as an example.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] However, the size of a datagram is not authenticated.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] That is, if an endpoint receives a datagram of a certain size, it cannot know that the sender sent the datagram at the same size.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A client MUST expand the payload of all UDP datagrams carrying Initial packets to at least the smallest allowed maximum datagram size of 1200 bytes by adding PADDING frames to the Initial packet or by coalescing the Initial packet; see Section 12.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Initial packets can even be coalesced with invalid packets, which a receiver will discard.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Sending UDP datagrams of this size ensures that the network path supports a reasonable Path Maximum Transmission Unit (PMTU), in both directions.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] A server MUST discard an Initial packet that is carried in a UDP datagram with a payload that is smaller than the smallest allowed maximum datagram size of 1200 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The PMTU is the maximum size of the entire IP packet, including the IP header, UDP header, and UDP payload.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The UDP payload includes one or more QUIC packet headers and protected payloads.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The PMTU can depend on path characteristics and can therefore change over time.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint SHOULD use DPLPMTUD (Section 14.3) or PMTUD (Section 14.2.1) to determine whether the path to a destination will support a desired maximum datagram size without fragmentation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Both DPLPMTUD and PMTUD send datagrams that are larger than the current maximum datagram size, referred to as PMTU probes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Each pair of local and remote addresses could have a different PMTU.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] PMTUD [RFC1191] [RFC8201] relies on reception of ICMP messages (that is, IPv6 Packet Too Big (PTB) messages) that indicate when an IP packet is dropped because it is larger than the local router MTU.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] DPLPMTUD can also optionally use these messages.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This use of ICMP messages is potentially vulnerable to attacks by entities that cannot observe packets but might successfully guess the addresses used on the path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The requirements for generating ICMP [RFC1812] [RFC4443] state that the quoted packet should contain as much of the original packet as possible without exceeding the minimum MTU for the IP version.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC endpoints using PMTUD SHOULD validate ICMP messages to protect from packet injection as specified in [RFC8201] and Section 5.2 of [RFC8085].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This validation SHOULD use the quoted packet supplied in the payload of an ICMP message to associate the message with a corresponding transport connection (see Section 4.6.1 of [DPLPMTUD]).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] ICMP message validation MUST include matching IP addresses and UDP ports [RFC8085] and, when possible, connection IDs to an active QUIC session.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint MUST NOT increase the PMTU based on ICMP messages; see Item 6 in Section 3 of [DPLPMTUD].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] DPLPMTUD [DPLPMTUD] relies on tracking loss or acknowledgment of QUIC packets that are carried in PMTU probes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Endpoints SHOULD set the initial value of BASE_PLPMTU (Section 5.1 of [DPLPMTUD]) to be consistent with QUIC's smallest allowed maximum datagram size.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC endpoints implementing DPLPMTUD maintain a DPLPMTUD Maximum Packet Size (MPS) (Section 4.4 of [DPLPMTUD]) for each combination of local and remote IP addresses.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] From the perspective of DPLPMTUD, QUIC is an acknowledged Packetization Layer (PL).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] An endpoint using DPLPMTUD requires the validation of any received ICMP PTB message before using the PTB information, as defined in Section 4.6 of [DPLPMTUD].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Endpoints could limit the content of PMTU probes to PING and PADDING frames, since packets that are larger than the current maximum datagram size are more likely to be dropped by the network.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Loss of a QUIC packet that is carried in a PMTU probe is therefore not a reliable indication of congestion and SHOULD NOT trigger a congestion control reaction; see Item 7 in Section 3 of [DPLPMTUD].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Endpoints that rely on the Destination Connection ID field for routing incoming QUIC packets are likely to require that the connection ID be included in PMTU probes to route any resulting ICMP messages (Section 14.2.1) back to the correct endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] One way to construct a PMTU probe is to coalesce (see Section 12.2) a packet with a long header, such as a Handshake or 0-RTT packet (Section 17.2), with a short header packet in a single UDP datagram.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] If the resulting PMTU probe reaches the endpoint, the packet with the long header will be ignored, but the short header packet will be acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] If the PMTU probe causes an ICMP message to be sent, the first part of the probe will be quoted in that message.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The version 0x00000000 is reserved to represent version negotiation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Other versions of QUIC might have different properties from this version.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] Versions that follow the pattern 0x?a?a?a?a are reserved for use in forcing version negotiation to be exercised -- that is, any version number where the low four bits of all bytes is 1010 (in binary).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] QUIC packets and frames commonly use a variable-length encoding for non-negative integer values.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] The QUIC variable-length integer encoding reserves the two most significant bits of the first byte to encode the base-2 logarithm of the integer encoding length in bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p05] This means that integers are encoded on 1, 2, 4, or 8 bytes and can encode 6-, 14-, 30-, or 62-bit values, respectively.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] All numeric values are encoded in network byte order (that is, big endian), and all field sizes are in bits.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Packet numbers are integers in the range 0 to 262-1 (Section 12.3).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] When present in long or short packet headers, they are encoded in 1 to 4 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] After an acknowledgment is received for a packet number space, the sender MUST use a packet number size able to represent more than twice as large a range as the difference between the largest acknowledged packet number and the packet number being sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A peer receiving the packet will then correctly decode the packet number, unless the packet is delayed in transit such that it arrives after many higher-numbered packets have been received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] As a result, the size of the packet number encoding is at least one bit more than the base-2 logarithm of the number of contiguous unacknowledged packet numbers, including the new packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] At a receiver, protection of the packet number is removed prior to recovering the full packet number.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The full packet number is then reconstructed based on the number of significant bits present, the value of those bits, and the largest packet number received in a successfully authenticated packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Once header protection is removed, the packet number is decoded by finding the packet number value that is closest to the next expected packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The next expected packet is the highest received packet number plus one.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Long headers are used for packets that are sent prior to the establishment of 1-RTT keys.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Once 1-RTT keys are available, a sender switches to sending packets using the short header (Section 17.3).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The long form allows for special packets -- such as the Version Negotiation packet -- to be represented in this uniform fixed-length packet format.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The next bit (0x40) of byte 0 is set to 1, unless the packet is a Version Negotiation packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Packets containing a zero value for this bit are not valid packets in this version and MUST be discarded.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The next two bits (those with a mask of 0x30) of byte 0 contain a packet type.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The QUIC Version is a 32-bit field that follows the first byte.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The byte following the version contains the length in bytes of the Destination Connection ID field that follows it.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This length is encoded as an 8-bit unsigned integer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] In QUIC version 1, this value MUST NOT exceed 20 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Endpoints that receive a version 1 long header with a value larger than 20 MUST drop the packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Destination Connection ID field follows the Destination Connection ID Length field, which indicates the length of this field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The byte following the Destination Connection ID contains the length in bytes of the Source Connection ID field that follows it.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Source Connection ID field follows the Source Connection ID Length field, which indicates the length of this field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The header form bit, Destination and Source Connection ID lengths, Destination and Source Connection ID fields, and Version fields of a long header packet are version independent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The other fields in the first byte are version specific.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The interpretation of the fields and the payload are specific to a version and packet type.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Two bits (those with a mask of 0x0c) of byte 0 are reserved across multiple packet types.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] These bits are protected using header protection; see Section 5.4 of [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The value included prior to protection MUST be set to 0.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] An endpoint MUST treat receipt of a packet that has a non-zero value for these bits after removing both packet and header protection as a connection error of type PROTOCOL_VIOLATION.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] In packet types that contain a Packet Number field, the least significant two bits (those with a mask of 0x03) of byte 0 contain the length of the Packet Number field, encoded as an unsigned two-bit integer that is one less than the length of the Packet Number field in bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] That is, the length of the Packet Number field is the value of this field plus one.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The packet number is protected using header protection; see Section 5.4 of [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A Version Negotiation packet is inherently not version specific.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Version Negotiation packet is a response to a client packet that contains a version that is not supported by the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The value in the Unused field is set to an arbitrary value by the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Clients MUST ignore the value of this field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Where QUIC might be multiplexed with other protocols (see [RFC7983]), servers SHOULD set the most significant bit of this field (0x40) to 1 so that Version Negotiation packets appear to have the Fixed Bit field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The server MUST include the value from the Source Connection ID field of the packet it receives in the Destination Connection ID field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The value for Source Connection ID MUST be copied from the Destination Connection ID of the received packet, which is initially randomly selected by a client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Future versions of QUIC could have different requirements for the lengths of connection IDs.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] In particular, connection IDs might have a smaller minimum length or a greater maximum length.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A Version Negotiation packet is not acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Version Negotiation packet does not include the Packet Number and Length fields present in other packets that use the long header form.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] An Initial packet uses long headers with a type value of 0x00.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Initial packet contains a long header as well as the Length and Packet Number fields; see Section 17.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The first byte contains the Reserved and Packet Number Length bits; see also Section 17.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A variable-length integer specifying the length of the Token field, in bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] In order to prevent tampering by version-unaware middleboxes, Initial packets are protected with connection- and version-specific keys (Initial keys) as described in [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The client and server use the Initial packet type for any packet that contains an initial cryptographic handshake message.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server sends its first Initial packet in response to a client Initial.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server MAY send multiple Initial packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The payload of an Initial packet includes a CRYPTO frame (or frames) containing a cryptographic handshake message, ACK frames, or both.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] PING, PADDING, and CONNECTION_CLOSE frames of type 0x1c are also permitted.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The first packet sent by a client always includes a CRYPTO frame that contains the start or all of the first cryptographic handshake message.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Note that if the server sends a TLS HelloRetryRequest (see Section 4.7 of [QUIC-TLS]), the client will send another series of Initial packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client stops both sending and processing Initial packets when it sends its first Handshake packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server stops sending and processing Initial packets when it receives its first Handshake packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Though packets might still be in flight or awaiting acknowledgment, no further Initial packets need to be exchanged beyond this point.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A 0-RTT packet uses long headers with a type value of 0x01, followed by the Length and Packet Number fields; see Section 17.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The first byte contains the Reserved and Packet Number Length bits; see Section 17.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A 0-RTT packet is used to carry "early" data from the client to the server as part of the first flight, prior to handshake completion.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] After a client receives a Retry packet, 0-RTT packets are likely to have been lost or discarded by the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client SHOULD attempt to resend data in 0-RTT packets after it sends a new Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client MUST NOT send 0-RTT packets once it starts processing 1-RTT packets from the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This means that 0-RTT packets cannot contain any response to frames from 1-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] For instance, a client cannot send an ACK frame in a 0-RTT packet, because that can only acknowledge a 1-RTT packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A Handshake packet uses long headers with a type value of 0x02, followed by the Length and Packet Number fields; see Section 17.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The payload of this packet contains CRYPTO frames and could contain PING, PADDING, or ACK frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Handshake packets MAY contain CONNECTION_CLOSE frames of type 0x1c.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] As shown in Figure 18, a Retry packet uses a long packet header with a type value of 0x03.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] It carries an address validation token created by the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A Retry packet does not contain any protected fields.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The value in the Unused field is set to an arbitrary value by the server; a client MUST ignore these bits.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The server includes a connection ID of its choice in the Source Connection ID field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This value MUST NOT be equal to the Destination Connection ID field of the packet sent by the client.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client MUST discard a Retry packet that contains a Source Connection ID field that is identical to the Destination Connection ID field of its Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server MAY send Retry packets in response to Initial and 0-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server can either discard or buffer 0-RTT packets that it receives.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server can send multiple Retry packets as it receives Initial or 0-RTT packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client MUST accept and process at most one Retry packet for each connection attempt.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Clients MUST discard Retry packets that have a Retry Integrity Tag that cannot be validated; see Section 5.8 of [QUIC-TLS].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This diminishes an attacker's ability to inject a Retry packet and protects against accidental corruption of Retry packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client sets the Destination Connection ID field of this Initial packet to the value from the Source Connection ID field in the Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Changing the Destination Connection ID field also results in a change to the keys used to protect the Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] It also sets the Token field to the token provided in the Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Subsequent Initial packets from the client include the connection ID and token values from the Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The client copies the Source Connection ID field from the Retry packet to the Destination Connection ID field and uses this value until an Initial packet with an updated value is received; see Section 7.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Other than updating the Destination Connection ID and Token fields, the Initial packet sent by the client is subject to the same restrictions as the first Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client MUST use the same cryptographic handshake message it included in this packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server MAY treat a packet that contains a different cryptographic handshake message as a connection error or discard it.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client MUST NOT reset the packet number for any packet number space after processing a Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] In particular, 0-RTT packets contain confidential information that will most likely be retransmitted on receiving a Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The keys used to protect these new 0-RTT packets will not change as a result of responding to a Retry packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] However, the data sent in these packets could be different than what was sent earlier.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Sending these new packets with the same packet number is likely to compromise the packet protection for those packets because the same key and nonce could be used to protect different content.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A 1-RTT packet uses a short packet header.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The next bit (0x40) of byte 0 is set to 1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The next two bits (those with a mask of 0x18) of byte 0 are reserved.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] An endpoint MUST treat receipt of a packet that has a non-zero value for these bits, after removing both packet and header protection, as a connection error of type PROTOCOL_VIOLATION.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The next bit (0x04) of byte 0 indicates the key phase, which allows a recipient of a packet to identify the packet protection keys that are used to protect the packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The least significant two bits (those with a mask of 0x03) of byte 0 contain the length of the Packet Number field, encoded as an unsigned two-bit integer that is one less than the length of the Packet Number field in bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Destination Connection ID is a connection ID that is chosen by the intended recipient of the packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Packet Number field is 1 to 4 bytes long.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The length of the Packet Number field is encoded in Packet Number Length field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The header form bit and the Destination Connection ID field of a short header packet are version independent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The remaining fields are specific to the selected QUIC version.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The latency spin bit, which is defined for 1-RTT packets (Section 17.3.1), enables passive latency monitoring from observation points on the network path throughout the duration of a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The server reflects the spin value received, while the client "spins" it after one RTT.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The spin bit is only present in 1-RTT packets, since it is possible to measure the initial RTT of a connection by observing the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Therefore, the spin bit is available after version negotiation and connection establishment are completed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The spin bit is an OPTIONAL feature of this version of QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Each endpoint unilaterally decides if the spin bit is enabled or disabled for a connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Implementations MUST allow administrators of clients and servers to disable the spin bit either globally or on a per-connection basis.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] When the spin bit is disabled, endpoints MAY set the spin bit to any value and MUST ignore any incoming value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] If the spin bit is enabled for the connection, the endpoint maintains a spin value for each network path and sets the spin bit in the packet header to the currently stored value when a 1-RTT packet is sent on that path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The spin value is initialized to 0 in the endpoint for each network path.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The extension_data field of the quic_transport_parameters extension defined in [QUIC-TLS] contains the QUIC transport parameters.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Transport parameters with an identifier of the form `31 * N + 27` for integer values of N are reserved to exercise the requirement that unknown transport parameters be ignored.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Many transport parameters listed here have integer values.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Those transport parameters that are identified as integers use a variable-length integer encoding; see Section 16.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This parameter is the value of the Destination Connection ID field from the first Initial packet sent by the client; see Section 7.3.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The maximum idle timeout is a value in milliseconds that is encoded as an integer; see (Section 10.1).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A stateless reset token is used in verifying a stateless reset; see Section 10.3.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This parameter is a sequence of 16 bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This transport parameter MUST NOT be sent by a client but MAY be sent by a server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The maximum UDP payload size parameter is an integer value that limits the size of UDP payloads that the endpoint is willing to receive.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The default for this parameter is the maximum permitted UDP payload of 65527.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This limit does act as an additional constraint on datagram size in the same way as the path MTU, but it is a property of the endpoint and not the path; see Section 14.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The initial maximum data parameter is an integer value that contains the initial value for the maximum amount of data that can be sent on the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This parameter is an integer value specifying the initial flow control limit for locally initiated bidirectional streams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This limit applies to newly created bidirectional streams opened by the endpoint that sends the transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This parameter is an integer value specifying the initial flow control limit for peer-initiated bidirectional streams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This limit applies to newly created bidirectional streams opened by the endpoint that receives the transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This parameter is an integer value specifying the initial flow control limit for unidirectional streams.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This limit applies to newly created unidirectional streams opened by the endpoint that receives the transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The initial maximum bidirectional streams parameter is an integer value that contains the initial maximum number of bidirectional streams the endpoint that receives this transport parameter is permitted to initiate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] If this parameter is absent or zero, the peer cannot open bidirectional streams until a MAX_STREAMS frame is sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The initial maximum unidirectional streams parameter is an integer value that contains the initial maximum number of unidirectional streams the endpoint that receives this transport parameter is permitted to initiate.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] If this parameter is absent or zero, the peer cannot open unidirectional streams until a MAX_STREAMS frame is sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The acknowledgment delay exponent is an integer value indicating an exponent used to decode the ACK Delay field in the ACK frame (Section 19.3).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] If this value is absent, a default value of 3 is assumed (indicating a multiplier of 8).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The maximum acknowledgment delay is an integer value indicating the maximum amount of time in milliseconds by which the endpoint will delay sending acknowledgments.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This value SHOULD include the receiver's expected delays in alarms firing.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] For example, if a receiver sets a timer for 5ms and alarms commonly fire up to 1ms late, then it should send a max_ack_delay of 6ms.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] If this value is absent, a default of 25 milliseconds is assumed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The disable active migration transport parameter is included if the endpoint does not support active connection migration (Section 9) on the address being used during the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] An endpoint that receives this transport parameter MUST NOT use a new local address when sending to the address that the peer used during the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This transport parameter does not prohibit connection migration after a client has acted on a preferred_address transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The server's preferred address is used to effect a change in server address at the end of the handshake, as described in Section 9.6.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This transport parameter is only sent by a server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Servers MAY choose to only send a preferred address of one address family by sending an all-zero address and port (0.0.0.0:0 or [::]:0) for the other family.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The preferred_address transport parameter contains an address and port for both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The four-byte IPv4 Address field is followed by the associated two-byte IPv4 Port field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This is followed by a 16-byte IPv6 Address field and two-byte IPv6 Port field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] After address and port pairs, a Connection ID Length field describes the length of the following Connection ID field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Finally, a 16-byte Stateless Reset Token field includes the stateless reset token associated with the connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Connection ID field and the Stateless Reset Token field contain an alternative connection ID that has a sequence number of 1; see Section 5.1.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The Connection ID and Stateless Reset Token fields of a preferred address are identical in syntax and semantics to the corresponding fields of a NEW_CONNECTION_ID frame (Section 19.15).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A server that chooses a zero-length connection ID MUST NOT provide a preferred address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] Similarly, a server MUST NOT include a zero-length connection ID in this transport parameter.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This is an integer value specifying the maximum number of connection IDs from the peer that an endpoint is willing to store.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This value includes the connection ID received during the handshake, that received in the preferred_address transport parameter, and those received in NEW_CONNECTION_ID frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] The value of the active_connection_id_limit parameter MUST be at least 2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] An endpoint that receives a value less than 2 MUST close the connection with an error of type TRANSPORT_PARAMETER_ERROR.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] If this transport parameter is absent, a default of 2 is assumed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] This is the value that the server included in the Source Connection ID field of a Retry packet; see Section 7.3.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p06] A client MUST NOT include any server-only transport parameter: original_destination_connection_id, preferred_address, retry_source_connection_id, or stateless_reset_token.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] As described in Section 12.4, packets contain one or more frames.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A PADDING frame (type=0x00) has no semantic value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] PADDING frames can be used to increase the size of a packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] PADDING frames are formatted as shown in Figure 23, which shows that PADDING frames have no content.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Receivers send ACK frames (types 0x02 and 0x03) to inform senders of packets they have received and processed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The ACK frame contains one or more ACK Ranges.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] ACK Ranges identify acknowledged packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] If the frame type is 0x03, ACK frames also contain the cumulative count of QUIC packets with associated ECN marks received on the connection up until this point.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Once acknowledged, a packet remains acknowledged, even if it does not appear in a future ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Packets from different packet number spaces can be identified using the same numeric value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An acknowledgment for a packet needs to indicate both a packet number and a packet number space.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Version Negotiation and Retry packets cannot be acknowledged because they do not contain a packet number.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer representing the largest packet number the peer is acknowledging; this is usually the largest packet number that the peer has received prior to generating the ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer encoding the acknowledgment delay in microseconds; see Section 13.2.5.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] It is decoded by multiplying the value in the field by 2 to the power of the ack_delay_exponent transport parameter sent by the sender of the ACK frame; see Section 18.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer indicating the number of contiguous packets preceding the Largest Acknowledged that are being acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Each ACK Range consists of alternating Gap and ACK Range Length values in descending packet number order.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Gap and ACK Range Length values use a relative integer encoding for efficiency.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Each ACK Range acknowledges a contiguous range of packets by indicating the number of acknowledged packets that precede the largest packet number in that range.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A value of 0 indicates that only the largest packet number is acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Larger ACK Range values indicate a larger range, with corresponding lower values for the smallest packet number in the range.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Each Gap indicates a range of packets that are not being acknowledged.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The ACK frame uses the least significant bit of the type value (that is, type 0x03) to indicate ECN feedback and report receipt of QUIC packets with associated ECN codepoints of ECT(0), ECT(1), or ECN-CE in the packet's IP header.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] After sending a RESET_STREAM, an endpoint ceases transmission and retransmission of STREAM frames on the identified stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint uses a STOP_SENDING frame (type=0x05) to communicate that incoming data is being discarded on receipt per application request.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A STOP_SENDING frame can be sent for streams in the "Recv" or "Size Known" states; see Section 3.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Receiving a STOP_SENDING frame for a locally initiated stream that has not yet been created MUST be treated as a connection error of type STREAM_STATE_ERROR.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A CRYPTO frame (type=0x06) is used to transmit cryptographic handshake messages.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] It can be sent in all packet types except 0-RTT.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The CRYPTO frame offers the cryptographic protocol an in-order stream of bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] There is a separate flow of cryptographic handshake data in each encryption level, each of which starts at an offset of 0.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The largest offset delivered on a stream -- the sum of the offset and data length -- cannot exceed 262-1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Unlike STREAM frames, which include a stream ID indicating to which stream the data belongs, the CRYPTO frame carries data for a single stream per encryption level.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An opaque blob that the client can use with a future Initial packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A client might receive multiple NEW_TOKEN frames that contain the same token value if packets containing the frame are incorrectly determined to be lost.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] STREAM frames implicitly create a stream and carry stream data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The Type field in the STREAM frame takes the form 0b00001XXX (or the set of values from 0x08 to 0x0f).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer specifying the byte offset in the stream for the data in this STREAM frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] This field is present when the OFF bit is set to 1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer specifying the length of the Stream Data field in this STREAM frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] This field is present when the LEN bit is set to 1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The first byte in the stream has an offset of 0.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The largest offset delivered on a stream -- the sum of the offset and data length -- cannot exceed 262-1, as it is not possible to provide flow control credit for that data.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] All data sent in STREAM frames counts toward this limit.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The sum of the final sizes on all streams -- including streams in terminal states -- MUST NOT exceed the value advertised by a receiver.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint MUST terminate a connection with an error of type FLOW_CONTROL_ERROR if it receives more data than the maximum data value that it has sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A MAX_STREAM_DATA frame can be sent for streams in the "Recv" state; see Section 3.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Receiving a MAX_STREAM_DATA frame for a locally initiated stream that has not yet been created MUST be treated as a connection error of type STREAM_STATE_ERROR.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] When counting data toward this limit, an endpoint accounts for the largest received offset of data that is sent or received on the stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Loss or reordering can mean that the largest received offset on a stream can be greater than the total size of data received on that stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The data sent on a stream MUST NOT exceed the largest maximum stream data value advertised by the receiver.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint MUST terminate a connection with an error of type FLOW_CONTROL_ERROR if it receives more data than the largest maximum stream data that it has sent for the affected stream.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A MAX_STREAMS frame (type=0x12 or 0x13) informs the peer of the cumulative number of streams of a given type it is permitted to open.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A count of the cumulative number of streams of the corresponding type that can be opened over the lifetime of the connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] This value cannot exceed 260, as it is not possible to encode stream IDs larger than 262-1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Loss or reordering can cause an endpoint to receive a MAX_STREAMS frame with a lower stream limit than was previously received.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint MUST NOT open more streams than permitted by the current stream limit set by its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] For instance, a server that receives a unidirectional stream limit of 3 is permitted to open streams 3, 7, and 11, but not stream 15.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint MUST terminate a connection with an error of type STREAM_LIMIT_ERROR if a peer opens more streams than was permitted.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Note that these frames (and the corresponding transport parameters) do not describe the number of streams that can be opened concurrently.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A sender SHOULD send a DATA_BLOCKED frame (type=0x14) when it wishes to send data but is unable to do so due to connection-level flow control; see Section 4.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A sender SHOULD send a STREAM_DATA_BLOCKED frame (type=0x15) when it wishes to send data but is unable to do so due to stream-level flow control.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A sender SHOULD send a STREAMS_BLOCKED frame (type=0x16 or 0x17) when it wishes to open a stream but is unable to do so due to the maximum stream limit set by its peer; see Section 19.11.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer indicating the maximum number of streams allowed at the time the frame was sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An 8-bit unsigned integer containing the length of the connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint MUST NOT send this frame if it currently requires that its peer send packets with a zero-length Destination Connection ID.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Changing the length of a connection ID to or from zero length makes it difficult to identify when the value of the connection ID changed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Transmission errors, timeouts, and retransmissions might cause the same NEW_CONNECTION_ID frame to be received multiple times.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Receipt of the same frame multiple times MUST NOT be treated as a connection error.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The Retire Prior To field applies to connection IDs established during connection setup and the preferred_address transport parameter; see Section 5.1.2.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The value in the Retire Prior To field MUST be less than or equal to the value in the Sequence Number field.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Once a sender indicates a Retire Prior To value, smaller values sent in subsequent NEW_CONNECTION_ID frames have no effect.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint sends a RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frame (type=0x19) to indicate that it will no longer use a connection ID that was issued by its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] This includes the connection ID provided during the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Sending a RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frame also serves as a request to the peer to send additional connection IDs for future use; see Section 5.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The sequence number specified in a RETIRE_CONNECTION_ID frame MUST NOT refer to the Destination Connection ID field of the packet in which the frame is contained.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint cannot send this frame if it was provided with a zero-length connection ID by its peer.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] PATH_RESPONSE frames are formatted as shown in Figure 42.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint sends a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame (type=0x1c or 0x1d) to notify its peer that the connection is being closed.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The CONNECTION_CLOSE frame with a type of 0x1c is used to signal errors at only the QUIC layer, or the absence of errors (with the NO_ERROR code).
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer that indicates the reason for closing this connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A CONNECTION_CLOSE frame of type 0x1c uses codes from the space defined in Section 20.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer encoding the type of frame that triggered the error.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A value of 0 (equivalent to the mention of the PADDING frame) is used when the frame type is unknown.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A variable-length integer specifying the length of the reason phrase in bytes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Additional diagnostic information for the closure.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] This can be zero length if the sender chooses not to give details beyond the Error Code value.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The application-specific variant of CONNECTION_CLOSE (type 0x1d) can only be sent using 0-RTT or 1-RTT packets; see Section 12.5.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A HANDSHAKE_DONE frame can only be sent by the server.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Servers MUST NOT send a HANDSHAKE_DONE frame before completing the handshake.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] QUIC frames do not use a self-describing encoding.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint therefore needs to understand the syntax of all frames before it can successfully process a packet.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An extension to QUIC that wishes to use a new type of frame MUST first ensure that a peer is able to understand the frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint can use a transport parameter to signal its willingness to receive extension frame types.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Extensions that modify or replace core protocol functionality (including frame types) will be difficult to combine with other extensions that modify or replace the same functionality unless the behavior of the combination is explicitly defined.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Extension frames MUST be congestion controlled and MUST cause an ACK frame to be sent.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The exception is extension frames that replace or supplement the ACK frame.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] This section lists the defined QUIC transport error codes that can be used in a CONNECTION_CLOSE frame with a type of 0x1c.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] An endpoint has determined that the network path is incapable of supporting QUIC.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] A range of 256 values is reserved for carrying error codes specific to the cryptographic handshake that is used.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] In defining these error codes, several principles are applied.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Error conditions that might require specific action on the part of a recipient are given unique codes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Errors that represent common conditions are given specific codes.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] Absent either of these conditions, error codes are used to identify a general function of the stack, like flow control or transport parameter handling.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p07] The management of application error codes is left to application protocols.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] The goal of QUIC is to provide a secure transport connection.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] A complete security analysis of QUIC is outside the scope of this document.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] For this purpose, attacks are divided into passive and active attacks.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Passive attackers have the ability to read packets from the network, while active attackers also have the ability to write packets into the network.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Attackers are additionally categorized as either on-path attackers or off-path attackers.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] An on-path attacker can read, modify, or remove any packet it observes such that the packet no longer reaches its destination, while an off-path attacker observes the packets but cannot prevent the original packet from reaching its intended destination.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Both types of attackers can also transmit arbitrary packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] The QUIC handshake incorporates the TLS 1.3 handshake and inherits the cryptographic properties described in Appendix E.1 of [TLS13].
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Many of the security properties of QUIC depend on the TLS handshake providing these properties.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Any attack on the TLS handshake that compromises the secrecy or uniqueness of session keys, or the authentication of the participating peers, affects other security guarantees provided by QUIC that depend on those keys.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Address validation (Section 8) is used to verify that an entity that claims a given address is able to receive packets at that address.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Prior to address validation, endpoints are limited in what they are able to send.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Computing the server's first flight for a full handshake is potentially expensive, requiring both a signature and a key exchange computation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] In order to prevent computational DoS attacks, the Retry packet provides a cheap token exchange mechanism that allows servers to validate a client's IP address prior to doing any expensive computations at the cost of a single round trip.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] An on-path or off-path attacker can force a handshake to fail by replacing or racing Initial packets.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] An on-path attacker can also replace the addresses of packets on either side and therefore cause the client or server to have an incorrect view of the remote addresses.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] The entire handshake is cryptographically protected, with the Initial packets being encrypted with per-version keys and the Handshake and later packets being encrypted with keys derived from the TLS key exchange.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Further, parameter negotiation is folded into the TLS transcript and thus provides the same integrity guarantees as ordinary TLS negotiation.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] Packet protection (Section 12.1) applies authenticated encryption to all packets except Version Negotiation packets, though Initial and Retry packets have limited protection due to the use of version-specific keying material; see [QUIC-TLS] for more details.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] An attacker that injects packets without being able to observe valid packets for a connection is unlikely to be successful, since packet protection ensures that valid packets are only generated by endpoints that possess the key material established during the handshake; see Sections 7 and 21.1.1.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] A spoofing attack, in which an active attacker rewrites unprotected parts of a packet that it forwards or injects, such as the source or destination address, is only effective if the attacker can forward packets to the original endpoint.
[src:quic-protocol/rfc9000-p08] An attacker can also modify the boundaries between packets and UDP datagrams, causing multiple packets to be coalesced into a single datagram or splitting coalesced packets into multiple datagrams.
